<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LoveLetter     11-26 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Love Letter,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Reads Love Letter Written By Dad 44 Years Ago</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Spelling of Karan in 2nd Graf is CQ</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A love letter that a soldier wrote to his
wife while he was being shipped overseas during World War II was
finally opened 44 years later by his daughter.
   ``It was a love letter from my father to my mother,'' said Karan
Johnson of Fresno, who opened the letter Thursday at the family's
Thanksgiving celebration.
   Because of a careless crew member, the letter Master Sgt. Morris
Johnson penned in May 1944 never reached his wife, Roberta. The
couple has since died.
   ``There are some fun things about the letter,'' said Ms. Johnson.
``His handwriting was so much better then. And opening it was
emotional.''
   ``It was very sweet. My father asked about the baby _ my older
brother Warren, had been born a month before _ and my father said
how much he missed the baby and how much he missed my mother,'' she
said.
   Johnson wrote the letter while aboard the USS Caleb Strong, which
was taking him and other servicemen to Algeria. A crew member was
supposed to mail 235 letters written by 92 soldiers when he got back
to the United States.
   But in 1986, a pest exterminator found the duffel bag full of
letters in an attic in Raleigh, N.C.
   James Althoff, president of the 781st Bomb Squadron Association,
spent two years trying to match the wayward letters with their
recipients. The association delivered all but eight of the letters.
   Finding Johnson's relatives was difficult because there was no
forwarding address for the family's San Francisco address. Althoff
finally learned from the Veterans Administration that Johnson, a
pharmacist, had died in 1966 and his death certificate listed a
Fresno address. Further digging led to the discovery of Karan
Johnson and delivery of the letter on Sept. 27.
   Ms. Johnson said her brother, who was on hand for the letter
opening, was excited about the contents.
   ``When my brother was in Vietnam, he was about the same age as my
father when he wrote the letter to my mother,'' she said. ``He said
he remembered writing the same type of letter to his wife.''
   ``It had a very sweet P.S. It said, `Dear Warren: Take care of
your mommy and I'll be around to check on you when I can.' ''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
