<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HotelBaby     11-26 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Baby,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hotel Baby Sent To Temporary Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUEFIELD, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newborn girl found wrapped in
newspapers in a hotel lobby received a new home for the Thanksgiving
holidays on Friday, but officials said the move might only be
temporary.
   A state social worker picked up the infant at the hospital Friday
morning to take her to unidentified foster parents, Bluefield
Community Hospital nursing supervisor Lisa Williams said.
   Callers from as far away as Georgia and New York, wanting to
adopt the baby or to donate gifts, continued to telephone the
hospital even after she was gone, Williams said.
   Publicity about the infant's ordeal led to such intense reation
that hospital officials did their best to transfer the girl to her
foster parents without the accompaniment of television cameras and
reporters.
   ``We kept it very, very quiet,'' Williams said.
   The abandoned child was called ``Baby Girl Doe'' by police, but
hospital workers renamed her ``Emily Robin'' or ``Holly Lynn,''
after the Holiday Inn where she was discovered Nov. 19.
   The Department of Human Services this week got court permission
to transfer the baby to a foster home. Hospital social services
director Jane Hood said the infant won't have a legal name until she
is adopted.
   The 6-pound, 9-ounce infant was less than two hours old when a
hotel worker who heard crying found her in a cardboard box tucked
beneath a hallway heating unit.
   The child, bleeding from her umbilical cord, was taken to the
hospital where she was treated for hypothermia.
   Bluefield Police Chief James Dent said his department has several
leads but still has not located the child's mother.
   ``We're not on a witch hunt for the mother to crucify her,'' Dent
said. He said it would be up to the Mercer County prosecutor to
decide whether charges should be filed, depending upon the mother's
reasons for abandoning the infant.
   One of the newspapers the infant was wrapped in came from
Christianburg, Va., Dent said. Bluefield sits on southern West
Virginia's border with Virginia.
</TEXT>
