<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 0156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     11-26 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Welcomes South African Move on Mandela</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department is welcoming the decision
of the South African government not to send African National
Congress Leader Nelson Mandela back to prison after his treatment
for tuberculosis at a private clinic is concluded.
   The government said that Mandela, who has spent 26 years in
prison, will be transferred to some form of house arrest.
   ``From a humanitarian standpoint, this is a commendable
gesture,'' State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Friday.
   ``We continue to believe that the unconditional release from
detention of Mr. Mandela and other representatives of opposition
opinion is essential to the search for peaceful solutions to South
Africa's severe internal problems,'' Redman said.
   ``We hope the South African government's decision to ease the
terms of Mr. Mandela's detention may be taken as a step in this
direction.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Talks Set On U.S.-Soviet Grain Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.S. negotiators is heading for
Moscow this weekend for another try at reaching a new long-term
grain agreement, the White House says.
   The announcement by the U.S. trade representative's office Friday
said the next negotiating session is scheduled for Monday. Alan F.
Holmer, deputy U.S. trade representative, will lead the delegation.
   Reports have circulated in recent days that an agreement may soon
be reached to replace the five-year pact that expired on Sept. 30.
It called for minimum annual purchases by the Soviet Union of U.S.
corn and wheat.
   Though the old agreement has run out, the Soviets have continued
to buy U.S. grain, including more than 5.9 million metric tons of
corn, along with some sorghum grain, soybeans and soybean meal, for
delivery in 1988-89.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Condemns Khmer Rouge Treatment of Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has condemned what it
described as the forced relocation by Khmer Rouge rebels of innocent
Cambodian civilians out of Thai-based refugee camps to areas close
to the Cambodian border.
   About 8,000 Cambodians were moved out of the Ta Luan camp,
controlled by the Khmer Rouge, in July and August and there have
been similar forced movements of additional Cambodians from other
camps more recently, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
Friday.
   Most of the remaining 2,000 or so refugees still at the Ta Luan
camp are aged or infirm, he said.
   ``We condemn this forced relocation of innocent civilians from
the relative safety of U.N.-assisted camps to more remote areas
subject to cross border shelling and lacking the necessary
facilities for the provision of essential services,'' Redman said.
   The United States has urged the Thai government to use its
influence to encourage more responsible, humane actions on the part
of the Khmer Rouge and it has done so, Redman added.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Salutes Books, Libraries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has proclaimed the
week of Nov. 28-Dec. 5 as National Book Week, saying a free society
``must prize its libraries just as it values its liberties.''
   ``Anyone who doubts the power or permanence of books need only
look today at countries around the world where the mere composition,
printing, binding and distribution of a book is a prosecutable act
of defiance against the state,'' Reagan said Friday in a
proclamation released during his vacation.
   ``We can all resolve during National Book Week to take stock of
our own reading practices and our attentiveness to sharing books
with others, especially the young,'' the proclamation said.
</TEXT>
