<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan by soul singer James Brown to put on a
show featuring wrestling and rock 'n' roll has drawn protests from
an Augusta police group, but a law enforcement group across the
border in Aiken, S.C., is happy. Brown, 55, is not on the bill for
the Dec. 4 charity event, which he is donating as part of his
probation. But the event's promoter, Jacque Daughtry, said Friday
that Brown will be present and might join the performers for one
song.
   The Police Benevolent Association in Augusta called for a police
boycott after members received complaints about police participation
in the show.
   But Ed Kaney, head of the Fraternal Order of Police's Aiken
chapter, said: ``My lodge has agreed to use the funds from this
event to purchase food and gifts for needy families within the CSRA
(Central Savannah River Area).''
   Last summer, Circuit Judge James E. Moore designated the Aiken
FOP to arrange the benefit concert ``for benefit of FOP and Helping
Hands,'' an Aiken shelter for abused children.
   The order was part of a sentence Brown, 55, received after
entering a plea of no contest to a charge of possession of the drug
PCP, and pleading guilty to resisting arrest and carrying a pistol.
</TEXT>
