<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 0218EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bush-Tate     11-26 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Tate,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tate Withdraws as Candidate for Press Secretary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The highest-ranking woman in the
Bush presidential transition entourage has served notice that she
doesn't want to be considered for the job of White House press
secretary.
   Sheila Tate, who held that position during the last six months of
Bush's campaign and has served in the same capacity as he prepares
to succeed Ronald Reagan on Jan. 20, said she concluded the job
would be too demanding.
   ``It's the total inability to ever have your own schedule,''
Tate, 47, said in a telephone interview Friday from the transition
office in Washington. ``I found myself in almost a permanent bad
mood, thinking about what did I want to do.''
   As press secretary to the transition, Tate had one of the
highest-ranking jobs and one with a high profile, and there had been
speculation that the former public relations executive was in line
to become the first woman to become press secretary to a president.
   ``I have no idea what he'll do at this point,'' Tate said, when
asked to speculate on where Bush would turn for a press secretary.
   There has been little public speculation about that position,
although the names of former Bush press secretary Peter Teeley,
Newsweek correspondent Thomas DeFrank and Cable News Network
anchorman Bernard Shaw have been mentioned.
   Meanwhile, Bush's transition office released a list Friday of its
109 paid staffers as well as transition volunteers, who include
Bush's eldest son, George, and John Sununu, the designated White
House chief of staff.
   Tate was listed as a paid staffer.
   Tate said she informed Bush of her decision on Wednesday, just
before the president-elect left Washington for a short vacation at
his compound in Kennebunkport, Maine.
   Bush has said that he wants to bring more women and minorities
into important positions in government and in his administration.
   Tate said Friday that she did not think taking her name out of
competition for the press secretary's job would necessarily lessen
the chance that it would be given to a woman.
   ``There are plenty of qualified women,'' she said, `` ... (so) I
don't take it upon myself that it is less likely.''
   ``He'll find the best people for the jobs,'' said Tate, who
served as Nancy Reagan's press secretary in the White House East
Wing from 1981-1985.
   ``I know that a lot of them (Bush appointments) will be women and
a lot of them will be minorities,'' she said.
   Tate said that the job of press secretary is particularly
grueling, and said, ``I just have so much going on. I've worked in
the White House. ... I do not want to go back.''
   She said she had no immediate career plans after she completes
her assignment as chief spokeswoman for the transition, but said she
wants to spend more time with her family.
   Tate said her son, Hager, is in his last year of high school and
that she and her husband, William, are building a new home in
McLean, Va.
   She said that Bush ``asked me my thought processes'' in deciding
to withdraw as a candidate for the press secretary's job and said
``he understood my concerns and we left it at that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881126-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 0229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Battleground     11-26 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Battleground,0851</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Once-Embattled Townships, The Fight Is Now For Hearts And Minds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORT ELIZABETH, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nowhere has the government's
counterattack against black militancy been more intense than in
once-embattled townships ringing this industrial port city.
   Bannings, detentions and deployment of army troops have enabled
the government to regain control of what some activists viewed two
years ago as the first ``liberated territory'' in South Africa.
   Monitoring groups estimate one-third of 30,000 activists detained
without charge since mid-1986 were from the Eastern Cape region
around Port Elizabeth. More so than in other areas, prominent
detainees remain in custody. About 55 local leaders are in their
third year of detention.
   The crackdown has been so effective that even underground
opposition activity is minimal, township residents say. But a spirit
of resistance remains, despite a government campaign to win good
will by upgrading services.
   Less than 10 percent of eligible voters here disregarded a call
by anti-apartheid groups to boycott recent local elections. Surveys
show overwhelming support for the outlawed African National Congress
guerrilla movement, which has many leaders from the region's Xhosa
people.
   ``This area has had the most resilient resistance to apartheid,''
said the Rev. Mcebisi Xundu, an Anglican minister. ``On the surface
it does seem the people have been made to lose their spirit. I don't
think they have.''
   In 1985, the peak of nationwide black unrest, Port Elizabeth's
anti-apartheid groups organized one of the most potent consumer
boycotts in South African history, prompting white business leaders
to open negotiations. Militant street committees held sway in many
black areas, sustained student boycotts closed schools, even the
security forces sometimes could not move freely.
   In June 1986, the government declared a national state of
emergency: activists were jailed, the townships sealed off with
barbed wire and checkpoints.
   ``When they (the security forces) moved in, they assisted the
community to identify the government not as a savior but as an
enemy,'' said Mike Mjekula, staff member of a regional human rights
organization.
   ``The people decided to be quiet _ they were not able to fight
this overwhelming force,'' he said. ``Instead they adopted a more
subtle form of resistance _ they would not comply with the
government's wishes.''
   Like other areas where black militancy was strong, parts of the
Eastern Cape are targets of a ``hearts and minds'' campaign to
realize government hopes that better housing and services will give
blacks a stake in preserving the status quo.
   ``The government has done sterling work, building new suburbs,
trying to uplift people,'' said Sakkie Louw, a Port Elizabeth
legislator from the governing National Party. ``Once a man has a
good home, a good roof over his head, he will be a different man
from the one living under plastic bags, not having basic things like
water and electricity.''
   In two new townships for middle-class blacks, the government
seems to have won over some residents, mostly civil servants.
   ``They now have something to lose,'' said Judy Chalmers, regional
coordinator of the Black Sash civil rights group. ``They're not
going to want to be involved in the next wave of unrest if they can
possibly avoid it.''
   In older, larger townships, she said, ``There's a feeling of
waiting.''
   ``Everybody is quite relieved to have a respite from the horrors
of 1985-86. The kids are back in school, the leaders are in
detention. But the hearts and minds have not been won.''
   For the moment, the new middle-class developments are a
phenomenon. Nearly half of the half-million blacks around Port
Elizabeth live in shacks. Most others inhabit aging, overcrowded
box-like houses.
   Some shantytowns _ Red Location and Soweto-by-the-Sea, for
example _ are among the most squalid in the country. Tens of
thousands of squatters live under threat of forced removal.
   A recent study calculated more than half of Port Elizabeth's
blacks are unemployed, the highest number for any major South
African city.
   The automobile industry, for decades Port Elizabeth's major
employer, has suffered hard times lately as sales were slowed by
rising prices. Thousands of jobs were lost two years ago when Ford
Motor Co. sold its operation to South African owners who moved the
plant to Pretoria.
   ``In many grim respects, the Eastern Cape is a mirror image of an
unacceptable future other South Africans will have to face unless
timeous action is taken,'' wrote Rory Riordan, director of the Port
Elizabeth-based Human Rights Trust.
   Referring to other experts' warnings that South Africa faces
recession and worsening racial tension, Riordan writes: ``We have
seen the future (in Port Elizabeth) and it doesn't work.''
   Bobby Stephenson, a city councilor representing the
anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party, said there are limits to
what Port Elizabeth's whites are able and willing to do to help
their black neighbors.
   ``Security is the first priority in the minds of most whites,''
he said. ``They were very frightened in 1985.''
</TEXT>
