<DOCNO> AP881126-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 0247EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Caribbean-Union     11-26 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Caribbean-Union,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Says Eastern Caribbean Must Form Single Nation to Survive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASTRIES, St. Lucia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prime minister of St. Lucia says
seven Eastern Caribbean countries should unite as one nation to
increase their economic clout and decrease the likelihood of coups.
   John Compton, citing the proposed U.S.-Canada free trade
agreement and the success of the Common Market, said, ``The longer
we hesitate (to form a political union), the more difficult the task
becomes as the determination of some of our members appears to
flag.''
   Compton, speaking at a meeting of leaders of the seven-nation
Organization of Eastern Caribbean States, is the strongest supporter
for combining St. Lucia, St. Vincent, Grenada, Dominica, St. Kitts,
the British colony of Montserrat and Antigua, which opposes
unification.
   The six supporting nations of the Caribbean organization signed
an agreement in July 1987 for political union, but there has been no
time set and little real action.
   Compton said the individual island-states cannot survive alone.
He said the vulnerability of tiny states was demonstrated this month
by a coup attempt in the Maldives off southern India, ``which
indicates the steps we should take if our countries are not to be
the next target of mercenary adventure.''
   Compton said the open market planned for 1992 by the European
Economic Community and a trade agreement between Canada and the
United States, to become law Jan. 1, ``should be an encouragement to
those who dare advance the cause of unity.''
   The two-day summit focused on political unity, proposals for
unifying the islands' police and customs, and an end to the use of
passports for inter-island travel.
   Excluding Antigua's 100,000 citizens, the six pro-unity countries
have a combined population of about 450,000. The seven
English-speaking islands already have an integrated economy,
including a common central bank and a common currency, the Eastern
Caribbean dollar.
   Compton said this week that even without a consensus on unity,
``those of us who are ready to go will move on and allow the others
to join along the way.''
   Of the six supporting members, the Leeward islands of St. Kitts
and Montserrat have been the most hesitant. The four Windward
islands, which share the region with the French-owned islands of
Martinique and Guadeloupe, have been the strongest supporters of
unification.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881126-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 0252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Earthquake     11-26 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Earthquake,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Hits Mountain Region Of Western China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake jolted an uninhabited area of
western China this morning, the State Seismological Bureau said.
   The quake, measuring 6.0 on the Richter scale, was the second
this month to hit the area of the Tanggula Mountains, a 19,680-foot
snow-clad range in Qinghai province north of Tibet.
   On Nov. 5 the bureau registered a quake of 7.0 on the Richter
scale in the barren area.
   That was followed a day later by China's most devastating quake
of this decade, a tremor of 7.6 on the Richter scale that by the
latest official count killed 730 people in southwest China's Yunnan
province.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded by
seismographs. A quake of 6.0 can cause substantial damage if it
occurs directly below an urban area, and a tremor of 7.0 is 10 times
as powerful.
   Today's quake struck at 6:29 a.m., the bureau said, according to
a report of the official Xinhua News Agency.
</TEXT>
