<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 0256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Iran-Rights     11-26 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Iran-Rights,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran To Let U.N. Human Rights Investigators Visit Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran, accused of executing 1,140
dissidents, says it will allow U.N. human rights inspectors into the
country before year's end.
   Reynaldo Galindo Pohl, the U.N.'s special reporter on human
rights in Iran, issued a report three weeks ago accusing Iran of
ordering ``a wave of executions'' of opposition members in July,
August and September.
   Iranian U.N. Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati said Friday
that Galindo Pohl and his investigators would receive the ``full
cooperation of the government of the Islamic Republic of Iran in all
respects before the end of 1988, for the purpose of carrying out his
mandate.''
   Australian Ambassador Michael Costello this week asked Iran to
``give a clear, unconditional and public indication of its readiness
to allow a visit (by human rights investigators) within a specified
period.''
   Galindo Pohl and the U.N. Special Commission on Human Rights have
never been allowed to visit Iran to check reports of abuses, and
instead have had to rely mainly on reports in Iranian and Western
media.
   Mahallati said Galindo Pohl's previous report relied on the
People's Mujahedeen opposition group, which he described as ``a
terrorist organization ... filled with the bogus allegations leveled
against the Islamic Republic of Iran with clear malice, purely
political and propaganda objectives.''
   ``It would be far-fetched to logically expect to find any truth
in their allegations concerning a regime against which they have
sworn enmity,'' he said.
   ``Therefore, we consider our call for full cooperation with the
special representative as a healthy challenge to him,'' Mahallati
said.
   Galindo Pohl's interim report cited mass executions in Iran from
July through September that included 1,140 political prisoners, as
well as other common criminals.
   The executions followed a July 25-28 raid into Iran by the
National Liberation Army, the armed wing of the People's Mujahedeen,
and Iran's accepted in mid-July of a cease-fire with Iraq. The truce
took effect Aug. 20.
   His report also said persecution of Bahai worshipers continues,
although some Bahais have been released from jail in recent months.
   Bahais are a 19th century offshoot of Islam viewed by most
Moslems as a heretic sect. The estimated 300,000 Bahais in Iran are
denied the right to practice their faith and cannot obtain higher
education or work for the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
