<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Rebels     11-26 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Rebels,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Attack Village, 22 Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve villagers and 10 rebels were
killed when guerrillas with automatic rifles and grenades battled
local defense forces at a remote hamlet, the government said.
   The Defense Ministry said Friday the attack shows the rebels do
not really want a cease-fire.
   A ministry communique said the rebels attacked El Guabo, 137
miles east of Managua, at 2 a.m. Wednesday. The rebels also wounded
four villagers and kidnapped a woman, it added.
   ``Contrary to accusations by spokesmen from the Reagan
administration blaming the Sandinista Popular Army for breaking the
agreement to halt offensive military operations ... the facts show
the contrary. Those truly responsible for systematically violating
the cease-fire are the counterrevolutionary forces,'' the ministry
said.
   Washington cut off military aid last February to the Nicaraguan
rebels, known as Contras, but continued supplying them with
humanitarian aid.
   The government and the Contras agreed to a cease-fire in March,
but talks aimed at a more comprehensive peace broke off in
September. Each side accused the other of violating the truce.
