<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0417 11-26 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0417,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Advisers Divided on Whether to Choose Tower For Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lead and reorganizes top 10 grafs; picks up 11th graf
pvs, bgng: ``Bush declined...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top advisers to President-elect
George Bush remain deeply divided over whether former Sen. John
Tower should be named secretary of defense, sources have said.
   Bush also sidestepped questions Friday about reports he would
back $3.5 billion to $5 billion in Medicare cuts, but he pledged to
zero in quickly on the problem of cutting the U.S. budget deficit.
   ``I keep reading in the papers a lot of things I'm supposed to be
doing that I don't know anything about,'' Bush told reporters on
Friday.
   Bush suggested he had made no decisions yet on budget cuts.
   ``Don't make judgments based on stories that don't really have
any authority behind them,'' he said.
   Sources close to the vice president, who spoke only on the
condition of anonymity, said the issue of selecting a defense
secretary remained up in the air. The sources said top advisers
remain sharply divided on earlier plans to fill the post with Tower,
the former Senate Armed Services chairman from Texas.
   Bush himself has given no clues on whom he might select, but in
recent days has appeared to discourage suggestions that it would be
Tower. In any event, Bush has said that he has not yet made up his
mind _ and that the decision will be his alone.
   Bush, visiting his family's vacation home, worked for several
hours on Friday in the small cabin he uses as an office but told
reporters he had no appointments scheduled during his Thanksgiving
holiday.
   Bush on Friday swooped into town to visit a wine and cheese
store, then went to a video store where he rented the movie
``Broadcast News.'' He also stopped in at a hardware store and a
golf equipment shop at a local country club.
   Spokesman Stephen Hart said suggestions on Medicare cuts were
``completely speculative. It's premature for anyone to speculate
about the budget.''
   Bush declined to comment further on news accounts, including one
in Friday's editions of the Washington Post, that his administration
would go along with some $3.5 to $5 billion in proposed Medicare
cuts expected to be recommended by outgoing President Reagan in his
final budget submission to Congress in January.
   Asked whether he would advocate chops in Medicare funding, Bush
said: ``My view is I'll address the whole budget problem very soon.''
   Bush pledged earlier this week to send negotiators to meet with
members of Congress on the first day of his presidency.
   That strategy was in keeping with a proposal by the man Bush
picked to be budget director, Richard Darman, that Bush not submit
his own rewrite of the Reagan budget, but instead work behind the
scenes with Congress to forge a compromise.
   Bush has insisted he will not support any form of tax increase,
and would seek to reduce the nation's $150 billion a year budget
deficit with a ``flexible freeze.''
   Such a freeze would hold overall spending at the level of
inflation, pairing additional spending in new areas with new
cutbacks in others.
   Bush aides have said that the only item not on the table for such
cuts is Social Security benefits, remarks that made it all but
certain that the new administration would advocate cuts in other
so-called ``entitlement' programs, like Medicare.
   Meanwhile, Bush aides said a meeting this weekend with defeated
Democratic rival Michael Dukakis would not occur. They said it will
probably happen next week in Washington.
   The Bushes had dinner Friday night at their home with Cardinal
Bernard Law, the archbishop of Boston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
