<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Cole     11-26 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Cole,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>112-Year-Old Portraitist Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alphaeus Philemon Cole, a portraitist, has died
of heart failure at the age of 112.
   Cole, born in Jersey City, N.J., died Friday at his home in the
Chelsea Hotel in Manhattan.
   Cole became a member of the Salmagundi Club, the nation's oldest
professional art club, in 1918 and was elected to the National
Academy of Design in 1930.
   His work is in the permanent collections of London's National
Portrait Gallery, the Brooklyn Museum and several universities.
   He expressed little admiration for Modernism and its progeny,
preferring the work of 19th century salon painters.
   Cole studied in Paris at the Academie Julian and the Ecole des
Beaux Arts.
   His father was Timothy Cole, a noted 19th century engraver of Old
Master paintings.
</TEXT>
