<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dukakis     11-26 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush And Dukakis May Meet In Washington, Governor Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis says he hopes to meet with
President-elect George Bush in Washington some time before he leaves
on vacation early next month.
   ``He has asked to meet with me (and) I am pleased to do that,''
the former Democratic presidential candidate said Friday.
``Obviously, I want to do everything I can to make this country the
very best country it can be, and that is true regardless of
partisanship.''
   Asked if he planned to give Bush some advice, Dukakis said:
``Well, I offered a good deal of advice during the campaign. He is
aware of that.''
   He added that Bush ``faces some very formidable challenges, the
most important of which is how to deal with some very, very tough
budget and trade deficits.''
   In an impromptu news conference at the Statehouse, Dukakis said
Democrats would be prepared to support Bush if he takes ``bold and
decisive action'' in social and economic policy.
   ``On the other hand, we are also concerned about our children's
future, about education and health care and housing, the environment
and the future of this country, and we want to make sure that those
important priorities remain important priorities.''
   There is concern, Dukakis said, that ``we don't begin balancing
budgets with cuts in Medicare and Medicaid and health care and the
kinds of things that, unfortunately, some people who are part of the
transition, are talking about.''
   Bush sidestepped questions Friday about reports he would back
$3.5 billion to $5 billion in Medicare cuts. The cuts are expected
to be recommended by outgoing President Reagan in his final budget
submission to Congress.
   ``I keep reading in the papers a lot of things I'm supposed to be
doing that I don't know anything about,'' Bush told reporters Friday
at his family's home in Kennebunkport, Maine.
</TEXT>
