<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Earthquake 1stLd-Writethru   11-26 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earthquake, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0421,0857</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Rocks Eastern Canada, Northeastern United States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with minor injuries in Canada, details,
quotes from U.S. residents. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY78, LaserPhotos BX7, QBC4,6</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Canada's strongest earthquake in 53 years
knocked out power and telephone service, buckled railroad tracks,
shook buildings and sent tremors from Michigan to Washington.
   About 50 people near the quake's epicenter at Chicoutimi, Quebec,
suffered minor cuts and bruises, but no serious injuries were
reported in Canada or in the United States. One American said he was
knocked out of his seat; others said windows rattled, dishes fell
from shelves and ceilings cracked.
   Seismologists said the quake registered 6.0 on the Richter scale,
enough to cause severe damage, but damage was relatively minor.
   Janet Drysdale of the Geological Survey of Canada placed the
epicenter about 90 miles northwest of Quebec City and just east of
the St. Lawrence River along a minor fault zone.
   ``It was pretty dreadful,'' said Irene Bouchard in Chicoutimi.
``Some of our picture frames crashed to the floor, our animals
started running about and then they hid themselves.''
   A shopper at a Chicoutimi shopping center said, ``Windows broke,
bits of ceiling fell. It created a real panic, people crying. It was
unbelievable.''
   The tremors knocked out power in Montreal and Quebec City and
elsewhere in the province but apparently caused more fear than
damage.
   ``We're on the seventh floor and I thought we were going to be on
the first,'' said Charlie Popejoy, 80, of the central Ontario city
of Orillia.
   In the United States, the quake was felt from the Great Lakes to
the Atlantic Coast and from Maine to Washington, but there were no
reports of damage.
   ``I was sitting watching TV and all at once I started feeling
dizzy,'' said Roy Tabikha of Cambridge, Mass. ``I thought there was
something wrong with me.''
   Peter Dehlinger, professor of geophysics at the University of
Connecticut, said the quake generated 1,000 times more energy than
anything previously recorded in that state. He said Connecticut had
an earthquake measuring 3.5 to 4 in the late 1960s in Long Island
Sound.
   Michael Luongo Jr. of Litchfield, Conn., was watching television
when the tremor hit, and thought he had a visitor.
   ``I was convinced there was someone behind my couch shaking it
for five, six seconds,'' said Luongo. ``I peeked over the top of it
(the couch) to actually look and shook my head in disbelief.''
   Gary Wilson was sitting in a chair on the second floor of his
Otisville, N.Y., home when the chair started to move.
   ``It was like sitting on top of a bowl of jello,'' he said.
   In Albany, New York Gov. Mario Cuomo was in the Executive
Mansion. ``I did feel it, very definitely. The chandelier shook. The
floor moved. It lasted about 10 seconds but it was something I'll
remember for much longer than that,'' Cuomo said.
   Clifford Williams of the Pennsylvania State Police said, ``One
lady called us and said she had whitecaps in her fish tank and her
chandelier was shaking.''
   Added Warwick, R.I., police Lt. Raymond Savoie, ``One guy had
complained that he had literally been knocked out of his chair.''
   The quake rattled Boston's Top of the Hub restaurant on the 52nd
floor of the Prudential Center while about 120 people were dining,
said maitre d' Stephen Brown.
   ``The entire dining room felt it. Everyone felt they were
becoming dizzy or faint. They all sort of smiled and looked at each
other,'' he said.
   Tremors began at 6:46 p.m. EST and lasted 15 seconds to two
minutes, Canadian Press reported.
   John Adams of the Geological Survey of Canada in Ottawa said it
was the largest earthquake in eastern Canada since 1935, when a
quake registering 6.4 on the Richter scale hit.
   Canadian Press said traffic lights were out in Quebec City and
that electricity was cut off to Montreal's central train station and
major hotels. Telephone lines also were down.
   Canadian Press said the quake caused the ground to cave in
beneath a railway track just west of Montreal at the approach to a
railway bridge. It said the damage forced Canadian National railroad
officials to shut down the major east-west rail line from Montreal
to Senneterre, 220 miles to the west.
   The tremors caused a fluorine gas leak at the Alcan aluminum
smelter in Jonquiere, Quebec, 25 miles west of Chicoutimi, but the
leak was repaired shortly afterward, the agency said.
   A foreshock was felt Wednesday and in the same southeastern
section of Quebec, the Charlevoix region, said Adams. That quake
measured 4.5 to 4.9 on the Richter scale. No serious damage was
reported.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake measuring 5 on the Richter scale can cause
considerable damage; a 6 severe damage, and a 7 is a major
earthquake.
</TEXT>
