<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TrainDerailment     11-26 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Train Derailment,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens Evacuated While Authorities Try To Control Ammonia Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRUITVALE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-five cars of an 89-car freight
train derailed during a heavy thunderstorm, and about 50 residents
were evacuated when anhydrous ammonia leaked from one of the cars,
officials said.
   Two people who were driving near the derailment were overcome by
ammonia fumes and were taken to a hospital in Terrell, about 30
miles away.
   The Union Pacific train derailed about 7:30 p.m. Friday shortly
before the National Weather Service issued a tornado warning for the
rural area. One witness said the train might have been hit by a
small tornado, but authorities were unsure what caused the accident.
   One car was spilling anhydrous ammonia, which is poisonous,
officials said.
   ``This is a hazardous material in a concentrated form. It's
pretty unhealthy,'' said Alex Tice, the railroad's regional director
for public relations in Omaha, Neb.
   A second car carrying anhydrous ammonia and one carrying
chlorine, which is also hazardous, were not leaking, he said. Three
empty cars of the 89-car train bound for Fort Worth last carried
sulphuric acid, another hazardous material.
   The train's four-member crew was not injured, Tice said.
   An emergency room supervisor at the Terrell Community Hospital
said the two people brought to the hospital would stay there
overnight, but were not seriously injured.
   The train derailed about a half-mile west of this northeast Texas
community of 400, about 70 miles east of Dallas. Authorities closed
the two roads in the vicinity of the wreck and evacuated nearby
residents.
   Lodean Tennison, dispatcher for the Tyler Fire Department, said
an estimated 50 to 75 people were evacuated. Tyler is 30 miles from
Fruitvale.
   ``We have about 45 or 50 over here,'' said Rev. Tom Pesnell,
pastor of the Main Street Baptist Church in Grand Saline, where many
of the evacuees went. ``There are some that have gone to stay with
their various families. There are some staying in motels.''
</TEXT>
