<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Floods,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Seek Survivors After Floods Kill More Than 200</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers used tractors today to excavate
villages buried in mud and search for survivors of floods that
killed more than 200 people and left 300 missing, an official said.
   Four army helicopters brought food and medicine to villages in
Nakhon Sri Thammarat, the worst hit province, said Saim Kaewsinual,
spokesman for the Fourth Army Region. Twelve southern provinces were
battered by a week of heavy rains.
   Saim said that by this evening, authorities recovered the bodies
of 236 people, mostly victims of mudslides that swept through Nakhon
Sri Thammarat starting Tuesday. He said 688 people were injured and
305 were reported missing.
   Mudslides destroyed 4,952 houses, 28 government offices, 221
roads and 69 bridges, he said.
   Water levels have returned to normal in many areas of the
province, Saim said.
   He said about 500 soldiers used tractors and other equipment in
the rescue effort in Nakhon Sri Thammarat's Phipoon district, where
mud and logs had charged down hillsides, slamming into houses and
crushing people. The hills were barren because of uncontrolled
logging and mining, officials said.
   Saim said about 1,000 villagers greeted Prime Minister Chatichai
Choonhavan as he inspected the damage at Phipoon district today.
   Chatichai promised food, medicine and new land for the victims,
he said.
   In neighboring northern Malaysia, the death toll from heavy
monsoon rains and flooding rose to 30 today with the discovery of
three more bodies, said the country's national news agency, Bernama.
   A total of 22,730 victims of the floods were receiving care in
emergency relief centers, down from an original 47,000, it said.
   The report also said life was beginning to return to normal in
the flood-affected regions. The northeastern state of Kelantan was
the worst hit.
   The Meteorological Department issued a strong wind and rough seas
warning for the next two days for the states of Sabah and Sarawak on
the island of Borneo, east of peninsular Malaysia.
</TEXT>
