<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Sami,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Health Minister Dead After Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's first health minister after the
1979 Islamic revolution died after an assailant stabbed him, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported today.
   Dr. Kazem Sami, 54, will be buried today, said the official news
agency, monitored in Cyprus.
   The assailant, posing as a patient at the doctor's clinic,
stabbed Sami in the head, chest and arms on Wednesday, IRNA said.
The doctor was unconscious after the attack and rushed to a hospital
where doctors operated for six hours.
   IRNA said the attacker has not been captured. It did not report
any suspected motive in the attack.
   Sami was born in the northeastern provincial capital of Mashad in
1934.
   He was imprisoned several times for his political activism under
the late shah, according an official Islamic Republic Who's Who. In
addition to his medical degree, he held degrees in psychiatry,
introductory theology and a master's in sociology.
   He was a professor at Tehran University and head of the
psychotherapy department at Raazi Mental Hospital.
   After the revolution, in addition to running the health ministry,
he was head of the Red Crescent Association, the Moslem equivalent
of the Red Cross.
   Sami was also an unsuccessful candidate in the first
post-revolutionary presidential election, the Who's Who said.
