<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO     11-26 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Says Warsaw Pact Has Many More Conventional Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Warsaw Pact has a massive numerical
superiority over NATO in conventional arms on the ground and in the
air, a NATO report said.
   NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner said the report, issued
Friday, does not show a more defensive posture on Moscow's part
despite recent statements from President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``I appeal to Mr. Gorbachev to match his words by deeds,''
Woerner said. The report also aims to challenge Moscow to issue its
own data, he said.
   The report, ``Conventional Forces in Europe: The Facts,'' does
not touch on the quality of weapons, only their numbers. Woerner
said the numbers indicate Moscow has the potential to launch a
surprise attack.
   The study is not the basis for NATO negotiators at the
Conventional Stability Talks, expected to begin in Vienna early next
year, he said.
   ``These negotiations will have their own counting rules'' for
conventional arms systems, that are more detailed and address not
just quantity of arms but also their relative quality, he said.
   The report cites East bloc arms systems Western allies will
likely want reduced, including tanks and other armored vehicles,
artillery, anti-tank weapons, air defense systems, helicopters _ as
well as overall troop strength.
   The study says the Warsaw Pact nations have a large superiority
in 11 major arms systems and that in eight of these the Soviet Union
alone outguns all NATO nations and its Warsaw Pact allies combined.
   The report cites these figures for individual arms systems for
the Warsaw Pact nations with comparable figures for NATO in brackets:
   Main battle tanks, 51,500 (16,424); armored infantry fighting
vehicles, 22,400 (4,153); other armored vehicles, 71,000 (35,351);
artillery, 43,400 (13,857); anti-tank weapons, 44,200 (18,240); air
defense systems, 24,400 (10,109); helicopters, 3,700 (2,419)
personnel, 3 million (2.2 million) and combat aircraft 8,250 (3,977).
   Rozanne Ridgway, assistant secretary of state for European
affairs, told a Washington news conference the report demonstrates
the Warsaw Pact has ``a substantial superiority'' in conventional
forces on the ground.
   She cited the ``massive forward deployment of armored forces''
organized and equipped for rapid and offensive operations.
   Alton Keel, U.S. envoy to NATO, said the report shows East bloc
nations maintain forces bigger ``than those of NATO in all heavy
weapons systems and that the Soviet Union retains forces all out of
proportion to those of any other European state.''
   The NATO study focuses on ground and air forces, since naval
forces will not be subject to the talks.
   Keel said he expected the 16 NATO and seven Warsaw Pact nations
to begin the conventional arms talks ``very early next year'' in the
Austrian capital.
   The talks will cover the territory between the Atlantic Ocean and
the Ural Mountains.
   They are to replace the Mutual and Balanced Force Reduction Talks
on force levels in seven NATO and four Warsaw Pact nations in
central Europe which have remained fruitless after almost 15 years.
   Steven Ledogar, the chief U.S. negotiator in Vienna, said Friday
that preliminary meetings on the Conventional Stability Talks were
deadlocked over procedural concerns by France. A new meeting will be
held next week.
   At issue is how to link the talks to the 35-nation Conference on
Security and Cooperation in Europe, which comprises the NATO and
Warsaw Pact nations and 12 neutral countries, officials said.
   France wants to link the talks more firmly to the Conference on
Security and Cooperation in Europe than the United States, which
wants the neutrals to stay away from East-West arms talks.
</TEXT>
