<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru   11-26 0779</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0416,0802</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Asks Forgiveness For Predecessor; Promises Reforms</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 4th graf, `Opposition parties...' with 6 grafs to UPDATE
with street protests. Pick up 5th pvs, `Roh stopped...' Edits to
trim thereafter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo today asked the
nation to forgive his predecessor, Chun Doo-hwan, and promised
amnesty and compensation for political prisoners jailed under Chun's
rule.
   ``I will liquidate past wrongdoings and carry out bold reforms in
the government and governing party in the quest of a new era,'' Roh
said in a nationwide television address.
   Roh pledged a major shuffle of the government and governing
Democratic Justice Party and a revision of undemocratic laws to
prevent more abuses.
   But opponents immediately rejected Roh's appeal and said Chun
must fully account for abuses during his seven-year term. Both major
opposition parties called for a full investigation.
   Thousands of dissidents and radical students braved freezing
temperatures and staged street protests in Seoul to demand that Chun
be arrested and punished.
   Students hurling firebombs and rocks clashed with riot police in
central Seoul. Police armored vans fired volleys of tear gas to
drive back students.
   ``Arrest Chun Doo-hwan. Punish Roh Tae-woo,'' protesters yelled.
   KBS, the state broadcasting system, said about 5,000 people took
part in the protests. Thousands of riot police blocked the students
as they tried to march through the center of the city.
   Police had no immediate word on injuries or arrests. Several
police officers were set on fire by firebombs.
   Roh stopped short of granting Chun a pardon, but he said any
prosecution of the former ruler would be unfair political
retribution.
   ``When he himself apologized deeply, how can we stone the former
president alone on the grounds that there were many mistakes in the
past?'' Roh said.
   Chun, a former general who took power with military backing in
1980, went into internal exile Wednesday after apologizing to the
nation for corruption and other abuses under his government. He
stepped down in February at the end of a seven-year term.
   Chun said he took full responsibility for misdeeds under his
government. He said he was surrendering all his property, including
about $24 million, in efforts to atone.
   Chun, living in a remote Buddhist monastery on the east coast,
listened to Roh's speech on radio but had no comment, an aide said.
   Roh, a former general and once close ally of Chun, is trying to
defuse public anger against Chun without damaging his own
administration.
   The Roh government is closely identified with Chun's
administration. The president took office in February after a split
in the opposition enabled him to win elections in December.
   Roh said the government would take the lead in exposing past
abuses and a special unit would be set up for that purpose. But he
also said he wanted the sensational hearings by the National
Assembly into Chun's government to end by the end of the year.
   The hearings have galvanized South Korea and helped fuel
anti-government protests.
   Roh said he would grant amnesty to political prisoners jailed
under Chun and restore the civil rights of those already freed. He
said ``generosity'' would be shown to opponents arrested under his
government.
   Government officials said the cases of 266 prisoners convicted of
political offenses or facing trial were being reviewed and as many
as possible would be freed around Dec. 10. Opposition parties
contend about 1,000 political prisoners are held.
   Roh also promised compensation for victims of the 1980 uprising
in the southern city of Kwangju, which was suppressed by the army
with the deaths of about 200 people. He also promised compensation
and exoneration for people killed or dismissed for political reasons
under Chun.
   He said political party funds would be put under open supervision
to prevent abuses, officials and politicians would not be allowed to
force businesses to make political contributions, special favors for
businesses would be ended, and undemocratic laws would be revised or
removed, including the harsh national security laws.
   Chun has denied any personal corruption, but some of his
associates and relatives have been convicted or charged with
misappropriating millions of dollars in government funds. Many of
the charges involve raising secret political funds, often by forcing
businesses to make donations.
   Roh said he would enforce law and order and said the violent
activities of radical students and labor activists will not be
tolerated.
   Radical students and dissidents calling for the arrest of Chun
have clashed several times with riot police in Seoul and other
cities in recent days. The radicals contend Roh is a continued front
for military rule and have called for his fall.
</TEXT>
