<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     11-26 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms In Mississippi Valley; Snow in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms spread into the lower Mississippi Valley today
after unleashing a twister and hail as big as baseballs in Texas.
Light snow fell in the West.
   Showers and thunderstorms prevailed from eastern Texas to much of
Arkansas and Missouri and Iowa and Illinois. Strong thunderstorms
extended across western Arkansas and eastern Texas.
   A tornado watch was in effect this morning for parts of Texas,
Arkansas, and Louisiana after a twister was reported in northeast
Texas Friday evening.
   Thunderstorms produced baseball-sized hail at Wills Point, Texas,
as well as large hail in eastern Oklahoma and high winds which
downed trees and power lines in western Arkansas.
   The storms produced locally heavy rains. Flooding was reported in
New Boston, Texas, which was drenched by 3 inches.
   The low-pressure system over eastern Kansas this morning that was
largely responsible for the severe weather in the south central
United States was also generating snow and gusty winds in the upper
Midwest.
   Winter storm warnings were in effect for much of Minnesota
through Sunday. Up to 10 inches of snow were forecast, as were winds
of 20 to 40 mph, which could reduce visibility and cause
considerable drifting of snow.
   Winter storm warnings or watches were in effect for parts of the
Dakotas and Wisconsin for today and tonight, and snow advisories
were in effect for parts of Iowa, Nebraska and Kansas.
   Snow advisories were in effect this morning for the western
plains of Montana, the mountains and western valleys of Utah, the
northern and central mountains of Arizona, and the mountains and
northwest plateau of New Mexico.
   Today's forecast called for severe thunderstorms and tornadoes
from eastern Texas to the central Gulf Coast states, with a lesser
threat of severe weather in Tennessee and the lower Ohio Valley;
rain across much of the Great Lakes region; snow from the upper
Mississippi Valley to the middle Missouri Valley, with the heaviest
snow expected in central and southern Minnesota; and scattered snow
from the northern Rockies to the Arizona mountains.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 60s or 70s across much of
the nation east of the Mississippi River; 30s or 40s generally west
of the Mississippi; 40s and 50s from New England into the lower
Great Lakes; 80s in southern Florida and southern Texas; 20s in the
northern Rockies and Wyoming; 50s to 70s from northwest Texas into
south central and eastern Texas, and the lower two-thirds of the
lower Mississippi Valley; 60s from the central and Southern
California coast to the desert Southwest.
   The nation's temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 6 degrees at
Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 77 at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 51 fair; Boston 38 fair; Buffalo 49 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 50 fair; Cincinnati 53 fair; Cleveland 54 cloudy;
Detroit 51 cloudy; Miami 73 fair; New York 42 fair; Philadelphia 37
fair; Pittsburgh 49 cloudy; Portland, Maine 31 cloudy; Washington 39
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 25 cloudy; Chicago 53 cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 59 partly cloudy; Denver 24 foggy; Des Moines 38 foggy;
Indianapolis 56 cloudy; Kansas City 48 drizzle; Minneapolis-St. Paul
37 cloudy; Nashville 58 partly cloudy; New Orleans 68 partly cloudy;
St. Louis 55 thunderstorms.
   _West: Albuquerque 33 foggy; Anchorage 12 foggy; Las Vegas 43
cloudy; Los Angeles 53 foggy; Phoenix 45 rain; Salt Lake City 31
snow; San Diego 58 cloudy; San Francisco 53 partly cloudy; Seattle
39 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 28 fair; Toronto 30 foggy.
</TEXT>
