<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FoodPoisoning     11-26 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Food Poisoning,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Dead Following Thanksgiving Food Poisoning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT VERNON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials were trying to determine what
was wrong with a Thanksgiving-style eaten by a 61-year-old
psychiatric patient who died, another who was in intensive care and
nearly 100 other people who fell ill.
   The victims were part of a group of about 200 outpatients from
Rockland Psychiatric Center in Nyack, Westchester County Health
Department spokeswoman Nancy McPartlin said Friday.
   The meals were prepared by a caterer and served Wednesday at
facilities in Mount Vernon, Yonkers and Tuckahoe, all north of New
York City.
   The 61-year-old woman, an outpatient at the center's Mount Vernon
facility who was not identified, died early Friday at Mount Vernon
Hospital after suffering food poisoning symptoms, including vomiting
and diarrhea, Ms. McPartlin said.
   The woman also suffered a heart attack, the spokeswoman said.
``We're not sure if it was brought on by the food poisoning.''
   Nearly 100 people were stricken, including 26 who required
hospitalization, according to Ms. McPartlin.
   The meals were prepared at an Iona College cafeteria in New
Rochelle that the Health Department closed and was inspecting, she
said.
   More than two dozen Iona students ate leftovers Wednesday from
the meal of turkey, stuffing and other traditional items, then went
home for the holiday weekend, Ms. McPartlin said.
   ``We want students who may suffer any symptoms to go immediately
to a doctor or an emergency room and to notify us,'' she said.
   ``So far we haven't heard from any of them,'' said Joseph Cullen,
a college spokesman.
   The food was prepared by Flik International of Mamaroneck.
   ``We will do everything we can to get to the bottom of this and
we are investigating every aspect,'' said company President Ruediger
Flik.
</TEXT>
