<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     11-26 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldier Wounded In Bomb Attack, Four Arabs Shot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian hurled a homemade bomb today at an
Israeli army patrol in the occupied West Bank town of Ramallah,
slightly injuring one soldier, the military command said.
   Arab witnesses said up to 150 Palestinians were detained after
the attack.
   Clashes today between stone-throwing Palestinians and troops in
the occupied Gaza Strip left three 14-year-old youths with shotgun
wounds to the legs at the Nuseirat refugee camp and Gaza Strip
village of Zawaydah, officials at Gaza's Ahli Arab Hospital said.
   A 16-year-old Palestinian who was seriously wounded in the head
was transferred from Shifa Hospital to an Israeli hospital, the
doctors said.
   An Arab reporter in Gaza said Palestinians clashed with troops in
Nuseirat and at an open-air market in Rafah. He said soldiers fired
tear gas and rubber bullets and that seven girls and women aged 15
to 25 suffered slight injuries. That report could be immediately
confirmed.
   After the bombing, patrols opened fire on the assailant. Troops
closed the area and conducted searches, arresting several suspects,
the army said.
   The bomb was thrown at an army jeep near several other military
vehicles in the central square, they said. The residents said troops
fired about 50 rounds of ammunition, mostly in the air.
   They said troops closed the area and grabbed 100 to 150
Palestinians, making them sit on the ground close to the site of the
attack.
   In a related development, a U.N. report released Friday decried
what it termed growing human rights abuses and frequent use of
violence by Israeli soldiers fighting the Palestinian rebellion.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar wrote, ``The overall
situation in the occupied Palestinian territories has worsened.
Civilian deaths and injuries continue to be widespread and so do
other serious violations of human rights.''
   He said he was ``deeply distressed'' by the high number of
casualties and by Israeli measures such as deportation,
administrative detention, curfews and razing of houses. He said such
measures can only aggravate tension.
   At least 315 Palestinians and 11 Israelis have been killed and
more than 7,000 wounded since the uprising against the 21-year
Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip began Dec. 8.
