<HEAD>10 Rescued From Burning Ship In North Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire broke out today aboard a North
Sea oil rig supply ship, but all 10 crew members were rescued by a
helicopter, officials said. No injuries were reported.
   The crew of the 2,750-ton Felderntor sent a distress signal to
the coast guard at 5:20 a.m., after discovering the fire in the
engine room, according to officials of the Offshore Supply
Association, the ship's owner.
   The ship was 80 miles northeast of Peterhead, in northern
Scotland, when the fire started.
   The crew members, including four West Germans and six Britons,
were rescued from the ship by a helicopter, said the
British-registered company, which is owned by the West German firm
Offshore Marine Service GMBH.
   The fire was brought under control as the ship was towed toward
Aberdeen, where it was to arrive Sunday, the company said.
</TEXT>
