<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines 1stLd-Writethru a0464 11-26 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0464,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bodies Of Missing Bar Hostesses In Aquino Assassination Exhumed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with eight arrested in massacre. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAPAS, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today exhumed the skeletons
of two bar hostesses allegedly killed in a military cover-up of the
1983 assassination of Benigno Aquino, the husband of President
Corazon Aquino.
   Also today, the military said the massacre this week of 17 people
in a remote mountain village was caused in part by a dispute over a
local cult.
   The remains of the two hostesses were taken to Manila for further
tests to determine if they really are those of two sisters closely
identified with the man originally thought to be the killer of
former Sen. Aquino, according to officials of the National Bureau of
Investigation.
   Aquino was shot to death on Aug. 21, 1983, at the Manila
International Airport as soldiers escorted him out of a plane that
flew him home from three years of self-imposed exile in the United
States.
   The slaying triggered protests leading to the February 1986
civilian-military uprising that toppled Ferdinand Marcos' 20-year
regime and swept Aquino's widow to power.
   Marcos and his military claimed Aquino was killed by Rolando
Galman, an alleged communist agent whom soldiers shot dead at the
airport immediately after Aquino was shot.
   But a civilian board that investigated the slaying concluded
Aquino was killed by one of his military escorts and that Galman was
simply used as a scapegoat. It described Galman as an underworld
character who was in and out of jail because of his links to some
military officials.
   The bodies were exhumed from a sugarcane field just outside
Capas,60 miles north of Manila. The burial pit was pinpointed by
five militiamen who claimed unidentified military officers ordered
them to bury the women in December 1986.
   The sisters, Anna and Catherine Oliva, were hostesses at a bar
frequented by Galman. They disappeared in September 1986.
   Officials said the five unidentified militiamen also pointed to
an area nearby as the place where they buried Galman's wife Lina and
cousin Rogelio Taruc in January 1984. The two were last seen being
led away from their homes by suspected soldiers wearing civilian
clothes.
   Galman's daughter Rosalinda said her mother told her as she was
led away that she was being ``invited'' by Gen. Fabian Ver, then the
military chief of staff and Marcos' most trusted general.
   Prosecutor Raul Gonzales said all four people were silenced
because they knew Galman intimately and were aware of his ties to
some military officers.
   Ver and 25 others were acquitted of murder charges in December
1975. But a new Supreme Court constituted after Mrs. Aquino came to
power ruled the first trial was manipulated by Marcos and ordered a
new trial. The number of defendants has increased to 40, most of
them soldiers.
   The military held a news conference in Cebu City today to present
nine people accused of participating in a massacre Tuesday in Bagtik
village. Gunmen killed 17 people and wounded 12 in an attack on the
chapel of a religious cult known as ``Katoliko Largo'' or ``Straight
Catholics.''
   The confessed leader of the attack said a cultist's refusal to
have sex with her husband led to the massacre, but the military
insisted that communist rebels also took part in the attack.
   ``I regret what I have done,'' Pelagio Caro said when he and the
eight other suspects were presented in Cebu City, 360 miles
southeast of Manila. The suspects, arrested Friday, will be charged
with murder, the military said.
   The military said Caro told investigators he resented his wife's
rejection of his sexual advances after she joined the cult and
``planned to do something about it.'' He said sex was forbidden by
the cult unless approved by its priest, Gervasio Sarita, a man in
his late 60s who was killed.
   The military said Caro and other villagers who opposed the cult
sought the help of a ``Commander Bador'' of the communist New
People's Army, who provided the arms and some of men for the attack
on the cult.
   Caro said the group wanted to punish only Gervasio and cult
founder and leader Cresencia Hermosilia, who was wounded in the
thigh. Caro said the group didn't intend a massacre and only fired
when cultists pelted them with stones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
