<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 1057EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0482 11-26 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0482,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amal, Hezbollah Fight Fiercely In Central Beirut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE casualty figures. Pickup 5th graf
pvs, ``Syrian troops...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite militiamen fought fierce
street battles today for control of Moslem districts in west Beirut.
   Amal, the pro-Syrian militia, pushed the Iranian-backed
fundamentalist Hezbollah, or Party of God, out of most of west
Beirut on the second day of street fighting, police reported.
   A police spokesman said 25 people were killed and 54 wounded in
the last 24 hours in the fighting between Hezbollah and Amal, Arabic
for hope.
   That raised the overall toll to 35 dead and 74 wounded since the
confrontation began in Beirut's southern slums on Wednesday. The
conflict for dominance of Lebanon's 1 million Shiites moved into the
central city Friday.
   Also today, the International Committee of the Red Cross began
withdrawing its Swiss staff from Lebanon, 10 days after a delegate
was kidnapped in south Lebanon. Red Cross sources, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the organization will shut down the
all-Swiss organization's operation throughout Lebanon if Peter
Winkler is not released by Dec. 3.
   Syrian troops moved into the city's Moslem sector Feb. 22, 1987,
to end militia chaos. But the 12,000 Syrian troops have done little
to interfere in the Shiite rivalry since it spilled out of the
city's southern slums Friday.
   ``We have no orders to intervene and put an end to the
fighting,'' a Syrian officer in Hamra said.
   Syrian soldiers manned their sandbagged checkpoints as usual. A
group in the Zokak Blatt area _ where the militias were fighting _
sat eating breakfast, drinking tea and smoking early today.
   A car filled with gunmen approached the checkpoint and quietly
crossed it. The Syrian soldiers watched and said nothing.
   The Christian Voice of Lebanon radio lashed out at the Syrians,
saying ``the whole justification for Syria's military presence in
west Beirut has collapsed. The Syrians cannot keep peace.''
   Both sides deployed mortars, rocket-propelled grenade-launchers
and .50-caliber machine guns across west Beirut's neighborhoods,
police said.
   Amal-Hezbollah clashes were particularly fierce in the gutted
hotel district of central Beirut and the adjacent former Jewish
quarter that has been taken over by Shiite squatters since the start
of the 13-year civil war.
   Stray shells hit several residential apartments, setting them on
fire and forcing panic-stricken residents to take cover in basements
and bomb shelters.
   Fires raged out of control in several buildings and cars as
firefighters could not reach the confrontation areas due to
intensity of the clashes, the police spokesman said.
   Smoke billowed from the Arab Academy, a private secondary school
in Zokak Blatt district, as Amal militiamen hammered it with dozens
of mortar rounds.
   The Amal-Hezbollah clashes broke out in Beirut a few days after
Hezbollah held Amal responsible for an abortive attempt to
assassinate four senior Hezbollah leaders with a car bomb in east
Lebanon.
   Amal had accused Hezbollah of assassinating its three militia
commanders for south Lebanon in an ambush in south Beirut two months
ago.
   Three International Committee of the Red Cross left Lebanon today
for Geneva, leaving about 28 in the country. The three had worked in
the Red Cross' Sidon office, which was closed Wednesday to protest
Winkler's abduction there.
   The office helped the war disabled and visited detainees held by
Israel. The Red Cross staffers are the only group of foreigners that
has stayed on in Moslem west Beirut and south Lebanon despite the
waves of kidnappings that forced all foreigners out of the country
in the last four years.
   Winkler, 32, was kidnapped by three unidentified gunmen Nov. 17.
No group claimed responsibility.
</TEXT>
