<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 4thLd-Writethru a0491 11-26 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0491,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three More Killed In Soviet Ethnic Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY38 of Nov. 25</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with three more killed. TRIMS. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers shot to death three Azerbaijanis for
violating a curfew in the city of Kirovabad, raising the death toll
from ethnic violence in the city this week to six, an official said
today.
   Chingiz Sadykhov, officer in charge of the Azerbaijani city's
Communist Party headquarters, said in a telephone interview that the
three were shot Friday for violating a strict, overnight curfew
imposed to quell disturbances between Azerbaijanis and Armenians in
the southern Soviet Union.
   Soldiers in tanks and personnel carriers continued to patrol the
streets, even though there had been no protests for the past two
days, he said.
   Three soldiers were killed in Kirovabad on Tuesday, after being
called in to protect the city's Armenian population from mobs of
Azerbaijanis.
   The Defense Ministry newspaper Krasnaya Zvezda said today they
were killed by a hand grenade thrown from a crowd.
   Sadykhov said about 120 people had been injured in the unrest.
   Protests ground to a halt today in the capital of Armenia under a
ban imposed by soldiers who were reported to be on nearly every
street corner and breaking up gatherings of even two or three people.
   ``There are soldiers patrolling everywhere, especially in the
center of the city,'' said Arpenay Popoyan, wife of activist Rafael
Popoyan in a telephone interview from the Armenian capital, Yerevan.
   ``If two or three people gather, the soldiers come and break them
up,'' she said. ``The patrols are very strict.''
   Mrs. Popoyan and correspondent Yuri Kankanyan of the official
Armenian news agency Armenpress said there were no protests or
meetings, which were banned by the military commandant under an
order establishing an overnight curfew.
   Most public transportation and stores were open, and ``no
excesses are evident,'' said Kankanyan.
   Musa Mamedov, information director for the Azerbaijani Foreign
Ministry in Baku, said in a telephone interview that demonstrations
continued in Baku but that there was no violence.
   Official Radio Moscow said the situation was ``relatively calm,''
despite attempts ``to provoke riots in several areas.''
   It said transport and shops were operating there as well. A
curfew remained in effect in Baku.
   Kankanyan said 500 Armenians, mostly women and children had
arrived in Yerevan from the Azerbaijani region of Nakhichevan, a
small enclave situated between Iran and Armenia, but that Armenians
were waiting for the first refugees to arrive from Kirovabad, site
of the worst violence this week.
   Mamedov denied reports of much higher death tolls from the
fighting in Armenia and Azerbaijan, including one cited by Soviet
human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov, who said in the United
States that more than 130 Armenians had been killed. Sakharov, who
did not give the source for his figures, urged the Soviet government
to take measures to protect Armenians.
   Reports of high casualty tolls are rife in the Armenian community
in Yerevan and in Moscow, but they have not been confirmed. Mrs.
Popoyan said activists in Yerevan also could not confirm reports of
more than 100 deaths.
   Mamedov said the figure of 130 included injuries and deaths.
   He said the majority of those injured in Kirovabad were
Azerbaijanis hurt in clashes with soldiers.
   The latest fighting between Armenians and Azerbaijanis has
challenged President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform efforts.
   Gorbachev, speaking in a joint interview with visiting President
Francois Mitterrand of France broadcast Friday night on French
television, said the unrest was part of ``perestroika,'' his
campaign to reform Soviet society.
   Animosity between Armenians, who are mostly Christian, and
Azerbaijanis, mostly Moslem, dates back hundreds of years in the
Caucasus region that now forms part of the Soviet border with Turkey
and Iran.
   Gorbachev said Soviet leaders would meet soon with delegations of
Armenians and Azerbaijanis seeking a ``solution that would conform
to the best interests of these two peoples and our country.''
   Ethnic conflict in the two Caucasus republics escalated in
February in a dispute over Nagorno-Karabakh, a territory with a
predominantly Armenian population that has been part of Azerbaijan
since 1923.
   Armenians held general strikes and mass demonstrations demanding
that the territory be annexed to Armenia, although they do not have
a common border, but Moscow did not approve it. A riot Feb. 28 in
the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait killed 32 people, 26 of them
Armenians.
</TEXT>
