<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EcclesiaAbuse     11-26 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecclesia Abuse,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Additional Charges Leveled Against Defendant In Church Camp
Beatings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A supervisor at a religious center
facing trial in the beating death of an 8-year-old girl has been
charged with beating nine other children at the camp with an
extension cord.
   Constance Z. Jackson was arraigned Friday in Clackamas County
Circuit Court on nine counts each of second-degree assault and
first-degree criminal mistreatment.
   According to indictments issued by a Clackamas County grand jury,
Jackson is alleged to have injured children under her care or
supervision ``by means of a dangerous weapon'' _ hitting them with
an extension cord.
   Judge Patrick D. Gilroy scheduled a Jan. 30 trial on the combined
additional charges. Jackson, 37, was allowed to remain free pending
trial next month on the first-degree manslaughter charge she faces
in connection with the death of Dayna Lorea Broussard.
   Dayna was the daughter of Eldridge Broussard Jr., founder of the
Ecclesia Athletic Association, which ran the camp at a rural house
east of Sandy where she was fatally beaten Oct. 14.
   Four people, all associated with Ecclesia and the Broussard-led
Watts Christian Center in Los Angeles, from which Ecclesia evolved,
were charged with manslaughter. Two, including Jackson, were
released from custody earlier this month while two others remain in
the Clackamas County jail.
   After the girl's death, Oregon officials took custody of 53
children found at the Sandy house. All remain in state custody,
although one has been allowed to stay with her grandparents, who
live in Oregon.
   Officials alleged the children were subjected to systematic
beatings and other abuse.
   Broussard has said his group relies on strict discipline and
athletic training to held children endure the rigors of ghetto
living, but he denies charges that the children were abused.
Broussard has not been charged in the case.
