<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Urban Guerrillas Kill Two Soldiers On Passenger Bus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds time element to 2nd graf, ``Shortly before...'' Pickup
3rd graf pvs, ``No group...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Urban guerrillas boarded a city
bus and shot to death two soldiers and wounded a third, authorities
said. One passenger was killed and three were seriously wounded in a
firefight aboard the bus, a hospital spokesman said.
   Shortly before the bus attack Friday night, a bomb went off at
the house of the mayor of the working-class suburb of Mejicanos, who
was not home at the time. Three passers-by were wounded by the
blast, said the mayor, Daniel Rivera.
   No group claimed responsibility for the bomb, which damaged
Rivera's garage.
   Violence is on the rise in this country, wracked by nine years of
civil war between leftist guerrillas and the U.S.-backed government.
   Urban leftist guerrillas killed a soldier on a bus and wounded
another Wednesday in the same kind of attack.
   A decapitated body was found Friday in the San Ramon
neighborhood. The body showed signs of torture. A watchman was
gunned down at midday Friday in the Centroamerica neighborhood.
   A third body was discovered just south of the capital. The
unidentified man had been shot through the head. His wrists were
marked as if he had been tightly bound.
   Local and international human rights groups have noted a sharp
rise this year in politically motivated killings by right-wing death
squads believed to be linked to the military. It was not immediately
known if the latest slayings were politically motivated.
   In the bus attack, two guerrillas opened fire on three army
soldiers on guard duty aboard the vehicle as it passed through
Libertad neighborhood, bus driver Ramon Jimenez told The Associated
Press.
   Two soldiers were killed, and a third soldier was wounded in the
shootout, authorities said.
   Jimenez said about 50 people were aboard the bus at the time.
   ``There was great panic. Women and children were crying,'' he
said.
   Jose Figueroa, spokesman at Rosales Hospital, said one male
passenger died en route to the hospital. He said three women
suffered serious' bullet wounds.
