<HEAD>Moderate Catholic Leader Calls on IRA to Drop Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a moderate Roman
Catholic political party accused the outlawed the IRA on Saturday of
``moral cowardice'' for using violence in their fight to end British
rule in the province.
   Social Democratic and Labor Party leader John Hume called on the
Irish Republican Army to put down guns and bombs and try to work for
talks to heal differences in the region.
   ``If they were to do so, then the atmosphere in this whole island
... would be transformed, and the nightmare of all our people would
be truly at an end,'' said Hume, whose party also wants to end
British rule peacefully and unite the mainly Protestant province
with the Irish republic.
   The IRA's choice of violence showed ``extreme moral cowardice and
a deeply partitionist attitude,'' Hume said at the opening of an
annual party conference. ``In their minds it is blood that is the
essential qualification for a patriot, not sweat.''
   He said the IRA had killed more than twice as many Catholics as
their real targets, the security forces, but did not give figures.
   Talks on Northern Ireland's future between his party and Sinn
Fein, the legal political wing of the IRA, broke down in September.
Hume's party blamed the impasse on Sinn Fein's refusal to renounce
IRA violence.
