<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Snatched, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0494,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premature Baby Snatched From Hospital Room</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with child found; two suspects in custody.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sickly premature baby snatched from a
hospital room was found 16 hours later in apparent good health,
officials said today.
   Catherine Cureton of the University of Michigan Medical Center
said two people were in custody in connection with the theft of
2{-month-old Debra Lynn Moore. She said the baby, who was taken
Friday evening, was found near Howell in Livingston County, but had
no other details.
   The baby had been hooked up to monitoring equipment at C.S. Mott
Children's Hospital, which is affiliated with the university. An
alarm went off when she was removed from a bassinet Friday evening,
but the baby was gone when hospital workers reached the room, said
police Sgt. Mark Jones.
   Sgt. Jim Tieman said an anonymous tip led Ann Arbor police to the
child, who was found about 11:15 a.m. today. She disappeared about
6:35 p.m. Friday.
   He had no immediate detail on the identity of the suspects or the
motive for the kidnapping.
   Earlier, Tieman had said said police were looking for a woman
seen acting suspiciously just before the baby was reported stolen.
He described her as a white female, about 30, with a heavy build.
   Debra's twin brother, in a nearby bassinet and receiving oxygen,
was unharmed, he said. Breathing difficulties are not uncommon in
premature babies, whose lungs may not have matured before birth.
   The 17-year-old mother was not at the hospital when her baby was
taken.
   ``She's quite upset,'' said Jones before the child was found.
Police, while releasing the baby's name, declined to give the
mother's name.
   Police early today ruled out as a suspect a woman who once worked
at the hospital as a security guard and who was seen in the vicinity
before the infant disappeared.
   ``We have chased that lead down and found out she was not
involved,'' said Staff Sgt. Harry Jinkerson.
   Police did not know how premature the twins were when they were
born.
   Debra was being taken to McPherson Community Health Center in
Howell, which is about 25 miles from Ann Arbor.
</TEXT>
