<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Reagan-Radio     11-26 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Radio,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Sees Protectionism Rejection In Mulroney Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today that the
re-election of Prime Minister Brian Mulroney by the voters of Canada
sent a strong message rejecting trade protectionist sentiments.
   In his weekly radio address, delivered from Reagan's mountaintop
ranch retreat near this Southern California resort city, the
president said that ``one of the key factors behind our nation's
great prosperity is the open trade policy.''
   Reagan had said earlier in the week that the victory by
Mulroney's Progressive Conservative Party will go a long way toward
sealing the U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement.
   When nations move toward protectionism, as the United States did
in 1930, Reagan said, it has resulted in ``disaster for the working
men and women.'' He said that in the wake of passage of the
Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act, one out of four Americans lost their jobs,
leading to the Great Depression.
   He urged Americans to ``reject the siren song of protectionism''
and said that, in the meantime, the administration would work hard
to see to it that U.S. trading partners ``play by the rules'' of
international competition.
