<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     11-26 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militants Attack Bus; Curfew Imposed Around Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militants shot and stabbed passengers
aboard a bus and fired on troops rushing to the scene Saturday,
killing six people and prompting a weekend curfew, news reports said.
   The curfew banned civilian movement on the streets around Colombo
from Saturday night until Monday morning.
   It followed the attack in Pannipitiya, a suburban neighborhood
four miles southeast of the capital, said Lankapuwath, the national
news agency.
   The news agency said the militants, suspected Sinhalese
extremists, launched the attack after boarding the bus.
   A woman passenger died after being injured in the gunfire, news
reports said. Three soldiers were killed aboard the bus and two
others died when they approached the bus after hearing the gunfire,
Lankapuwath said. The militants then fled.
   Soldiers have been escorting passenger buses in Colombo and its
outskirts after a series of strike calls by the People's Liberation
Front, a militant Sinhalese group, earlier this month.
   The front stepped up its 16-month anti-government campaign
earlier this month demanding the resignation of President Junius R.
Jayewardene.
   The front opposes an India-sponsored peace plan signed by the
government that was aimed at ending the 5-year-old war by minority
Tamil rebels for an independent homeland.
   The Sinhalese group says the July 1987 plan gives too many
concessions to the minority Tamils. The front has been blamed by the
government for about 875 killings since the plan was signed.
   At least 325 of the killings have taken place since Oct. 15, the
government says.
   India became involved in the ethnic strife in Sri Lanka because
of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils for the rebel cause.
It sent in at least 47,000 soldiers to quell the Tamil insurgency
after the rebels rejected the 1987 peace accord.
   Tamil rebels have been fighting for an independent homeland on
the island's north and east since 1983. The separatist war has
claimed at least 8,500 lives.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and claim
they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who make up 75
percent of the population.
</TEXT>
