<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 1256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OPEC     11-26 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Awaits Iranian Response; Postpones Meeting Until Sunday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new OPEC production agreement hinged
Saturday on whether Iran's oil minister could persuade his
government to approve it.
   Iraq's oil minister, Issam Abdul Raheem Chalabi, crossed his
fingers when reporters asked him to describe the prospects of the
accord worked out by the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
   Gholamreza Aghazadeh, the Iranian official, made a quick trip to
Tehran to consult with government leaders before accepting the
package.
   ``He is still optimistic,'' said an Iranian delegate, who was in
contact with Aghazadeh on Saturday morning. The delegate demanded
anonymity.
   The other oil ministers postponed resumption of their winter
meeting from Saturday evening to Sunday to give Iran time to
consider the plan.
   IRNA, the official Islamic Republic News Agency, reported from
Tehran that Aghazadeh said the nation's response will be announced
Sunday.
   The news agency quoted the minister as saying he would talk
Saturday to the heads of the executive, legislative and judiciary
branches of government. The report said he would discuss the matter
in a Cabinet session Sunday.
   ``Then we will inform OPEC of Iran's decision,'' he was quoted as
saying.
   The proposed deal would trim current production by about 4
million barrels a day from the present 22.5 million barrels to 18.5
million barrels in the first six months of 1989.
   It also would retain the cartel's benchmark of $18 a barrel.
   Prices have been running $4 or so below that because of a market
glut. The new accord is aimed at curbing overproduction and raising
prices.
   IRNA quoted Aghazadeh as saying the new production ceiling would
boost prices to a range of $16 to $18 a barrel.
   Each one dollar rise in the price of crude oil theoretically
means an increase of 2.5 cents a gallon in retail gasoline prices,
although oil companies do not always pass along the full increase.
   The ministers began their winter meeting Monday, then adjourned
for closed-door talks to try to end a bitter dispute between rivals
Iran and Iraq. The two nations signed a cease-fire in August that
ended their 8-year-old war, a conflict both paid for with revenues
from oil exports.
   Iraq had been demanding an equal production ceiling with Iran in
any new accord. Aghazadeh had repeatedly said no.
   But under the new accord Iran and Iraq would get the same quota
of 2.64 million barrels a day.
   Iran would retain its production share at 14.27 percent of total
output. Other countries would give up some of their share to bring
Iraq up to the same level as Iran.
   Saudi Arabia maintains the largest share at about a quarter of
the cartel's total output.
   Under the current accord, Iran has a cap of 2.4 million barrels a
day. Iraq was given a ceiling of 1.5 million barrels butignored it.
Analysts estimate its production at 2.7 million barrels a day.
   OPEC members are Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates
and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
