<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SantaInjured     11-26 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Santa Injured,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Santa,' Burned In Work Accident, To Miss This Year's Festivities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN LAKE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man this small town knows as
Santa Claus will miss his annual appearance in the park, his visits
to shut-ins and other Yuletide duties this year, forced by an
accident at his job to spend a month in the hospital.
   Despite the accident, Elmer Buller, 60, had hoped to be able to
don his red suit and attach a white beard for his Christmastime
activities for the local chamber of commerce, said a son, Walter
Buller.
   But doctors at St. Paul Ramsey Medical Center's burn unit have
told him he will be hospitalized for a month because of the burns he
sustained when he fell into a pit of burning wooden pallets at his
workplace, Balzer Manufacturing.
   The son said that in Mountain Lake, a southern Minnesota
community of about 2,000, ``Elmer IS Santa.
   ``He's always visited people who are shut in,'' he said. ``He's
always had a concern for others and a soft heart. He's going to be
missed around here for the next month.''
   In years past, Buller has made four or five appearances as Santa
during the Christmas season for the chamber of commerce, posing for
pictures and handing out candy. He also has portrayed the jolly old
elf informally at other gatherings, his son said.
   For his annual appearance in the city park, Walter Buller said,
``He came on a sleigh if there was snow, and on a fire truck if
there wasn't.''
   ``If he had a free evening, he would put on his (Santa) suit and
go to the Good Samaritan Village where the old folks are and visit
with them,'' said the son, 36.
   The elder Buller, a custodian at the farm equipment maker, was
preparing to add more pallets to the fire Monday when he slipped and
his left foot entered the flames, family members said. When he
pulled his foot out, his shoe had been burned off.
   Buller suffered burns over 25 percent of his body, mostly on his
legs and hands.
   ``People who know Elmer say they're praying for him,'' said
Walter Buller. ``That's what keeps him from having pain worse than
he's having.''
   When he was hospitalized, Buller's first thoughts were on keeping
a Dec. 3 appearance for the chamber of commerce, his son said.
   ``He said right away ... `Don't cancel it. Maybe I can make
it,''' Walter Buller said.
   But a replacement had to be found.
   ``He's had a tremendous amount of pain. But he's a fighter,'' his
son said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
