<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     11-26 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once again, high school economics teacher
Dick Gastler is fighting hunger with the mightiest weapon in his
arsenal _ a tacky old leisure suit.
   Four years ago, Gastler let his students at Denfeld High School
burn his tacky green leisure suit in exchange for their leading a
drive that raised $3,300 to help fight hunger in Duluth and Ethiopia.
   This year, he's asking students to gather aluminum cans for
recycling. The proceeds will go to Project Heifer, an international
organization that provides livestock for families in developing
countries.
   If students bring in 40 pounds or more of aluminum on a given
day, Gastler says, he will wear a less-than-fashionable rust-colored
suit with white stitching the next day _ ``or I won't wear it,
whichever way they want it.''
   The rust leisure suit, he promises, is just as tacky as the old
green one and just as sure to offend his students.
   He said a friend sold it to him. ``He tried to talk me out of it,
but I went ahead anyway,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD VILLAGE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Freda Poundstone has a
reputation for being a tough and even ruthless political opponent,
but she also is known to be a pushover when it comes to children and
pets.
   Thanks to her friendly persuasion, 18 beagle puppies that were
used as experimental subjects have gone to new homes.
   ``I think you would be surprised how easily people take to such
darling little puppies,'' the mayor said as the last eight to be
adopted were picked up on Thanksgiving Day at the mayor's home.
   Poundstone first heard of the homeless pups from her daughter, a
student at Colorado State University's School of Veterinary Medicine
at Fort Collins.
   The puppies, now 8 to 10 weeks old, got their start in life as
test subjects for puppy formula at the veterinary school.
   When the program ended, Poundstone asked permission to find homes
for the pups. For two years, she almost single-handedly has led the
Colorado Animal Rescue program to save unclaimed pets from
euthanasia in local pounds and kept them in a private kennel until
owners could be found.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MASSILLON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kaserman family's 1,168-strong fleet
of trucks makes no deliveries and earns no income. But the vehicles
also consume no fuel.
   Massillon Health Commissioner Rick Kaserman and his sons Randy,
13, and Kevin, 8, have a collection of 1,168 models, which trace
nearly four decades of changes in trucks.
   Kaserman says his fascination with the vehicles began when he was
a boy and watched his father go to work as an agent for a moving
company.
   He cherished the promotional truck models from his father's
company, and still prizes one of his earliest models.
   When Randy showed an interest in the hobby, the family renewed
its effort to collect tiny trucks and this year they have added 300
vehicles to their collection.
   Through correspondence, the Kasermans have made friends with
officials of many trucking companies. Several companies have offered
Randy a job when he grows up because of the exceptional knowledge of
trucks he shows in his letters.
</TEXT>
