<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FoodPoisoning     11-26 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Food Poisoning,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Trace Tainted Thanksgiving Trail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT VERNON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The kitchen where tainted food was
cooked passed an inspection for cleanliness Saturday as
investigators tried to learn why one person died and nearly 100
others became ill after a pre-Thanksgiving dinner.
   ``The plant was clean. There were no violations,'' said Dr. Anita
Curran, Westchester County health commissioner.
   ``Hopefully, we'll have an answer by the end of the weekend to
what the possible problem was, whether the turkeys were held at an
inappropriate temperature'' or whether something else went wrong,
she said.
   About 100 patients and staff members from the Rockland
Psychiatric Center in Orangeburg became ill after eating the meal
Wednesday at outpatient facilities in Mount Vernon, Yonkers and
Tuckahoe.
   Ina Duncan, 61, of Mount Vernon died early Friday at Mount Vernon
Hospital after suffering food poisoning symptoms, including vomiting
and diarrhea. She also suffered a heart attack, but it was not
immediately clear whether that was brought on by food poisoning,
said Nancy McPartlin, a Health Department spokeswoman.
   Another victim whose name was not released was in stable
condition in the intensive care unit at Mount Vernon Hospital on
Saturday, said Curran.
   The meals were delivered after being cooked in a kitchen at Iona
College by a caterer, Flik International of Mamaroneck.
   More than two dozen Iona students ate leftovers from the meal
before leaving the campus for the holiday weekend. Officials didn't
know who they were, and officials said none of them of them had
contacted the department by midday Saturday.
   Although the cause of the food poisoning was not immediately
identified, turkey is ``obviously the first thing you would
suspect,'' Curran said. ``Poultry is a very, very common source of
salmonella.''
   While proper cooking destroys the bacteria, food service workers
who handle a lot of poultry can carry salmonella in their intestinal
tracts, and can transmit it to food if they don't wash their hands.
</TEXT>
