<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-ANCPrisoner 2ndLd-Writethru a0536 11-26 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-ANC Prisoner, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0536,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Frees Two Imprisoned Black Leaders</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to CORRECT Mothopeng's age to 75 and ADD
background on Mothopeng's prison record. Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``The
decision...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today released
two aging and ailing black leaders who are colleagues of Nelson
Mandela and had been imprisoned for more than a decade.
   Harry Gwala, 69, a longtime member of the outlawed African
National Congress, and Zephania Mothopeng, 75, president of the Pan
Africanist Congress ``were released unconditionally on
medical-humanitarian grounds,'' the Prisons Service said in a brief
statement.
   Gwala was freed from Westville Prison in the Indian Ocean city of
Durban, and Mothopeng was freed from Diepkloof Prison outside
Johannesburg.
   Gwala spent more than 20 years in prison and was serving a life
sentence for his involvement with the ANC guerrilla movement, headed
by Mandela.
   He is suffering from a degenerative neurological disorder with no
known cure. He said the illness has left his arms paralyzed, but his
mind is clear.
   Mothopeng, who has been seriously ill for several months, was
imprisoned in 1976 and had been detained several times prior to that.
   He was a longtime member of the ANC but broke from the
organization in 1959 to help establish the Pan Africanist Congress,
which favors black self-sufficiency in the struggle for political
rights.
   The decision to free Gwala and Mothopeng is the latest in a
series of moves by the government that appear aimed at reducing
domestic and international pressure on South Africa. In the past
week, the government has:
   _Endorsed a regional peace plan that would require South Africa
to grant independence to South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   _Granted clemency to the ``Sharpville Six,'' a group of blacks
sentenced to death for complicity in a 1984 mob killing. The death
sentences, replaced with lengthy jail terms, had provoked
international protest.
   _Said Mandela, the country's best known black leader, would not
return to prison when he recovers from tuberculosis at a Cape Town
hospital. Mandela will remain in custody at a ``suitable'' location,
the government said.
   Gwala's daughter, Lulu, said earlier today that her father
remained a member of the ANC and the South African Communist Party,
which also is outlawed. She said she was not aware of any
restrictions placed on Gwala, but did not know if he intened to
publicly resume his political activities.
   Gwala served eight years in prison from 1964-72 following a
conviction on sabotage. He was arrested in 1975 and detained for two
years. In 1977, he was sentenced to life in prison for involvement
with the ANC, the main black group attempting to overthrow the
white-led government.
   Lawyers for Gwala wrote President P.W. Botha in July and pleaded
that Gwala be released because of his illness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
