<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-Jobs Bjt   11-26 0950</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Jobs, Bjt,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Said Ready To Turn To Commerce, HHS After Wrapping Up Defense</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As George Bush focused on his national security
team, job-seekers eyed the remaining top positions with some
speculating the president-elect would soon turn his attention to
vacancies at Commerce and Health and Human Services.
   John Sununu, Bush's designated White House chief of staff, said
in an interview broadcast Saturday, ``I think next week you'll see
action in a couple of areas associated with defense.''
   Aides at Bush's transition office did not have a schedule for
when the president-elect would make his next appointments. Bush
returns to the nation's capital Sunday after a Thanksgiving vacation
at Kennebunkport, Maine.
   Sununu, appearing on CNN's ``Evans & Novak'' show, also said he
has asked Robert M. Teeter, co-director of Bush's transition office,
to serve as his deputy chief of staff. ``He's considering it and ...
I would hope that he says yes,'' said Sununu.
   Teeter's co-director, Craig Fuller, has been asked ``to make
suggestions as to how he can make a contribution'' in the Bush
administration, said Sununu, the retiring governor of New Hampshire.
   While there has been talk that Fuller might head the
Transportation Department, Sununu said Fuller ``probably has a
higher likelihood of not being in...'' the administration.
   After Fuller lost out to Sununu in the competition to become
chief of staff, he said he would return to private business next
year.
   Teeter was out of town and could not be reached. His office
assistant said she did not know whether he had reached any decision
on Sununu's offer.
   There has been widespread speculation that former Sen. John Tower
of Texas is the front-runner to become the Pentagon chief, despite
questions about his personal life and his commitment to procurement
reform. Tower was divorced from his wife last year.
   Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass., a member of the House Armed
Services Committee and a supporter of eliminating Pentagon waste,
recalled Tower as ``strident'' in the Senate. Tower chaired the
Senate Armed Services Committee during the massive defense build-up
in the early years of the Reagan administration.
   Bush's choice must be someone ``dedicated to cleaning up that
mess at the Pentagon,'' Mavroules said in an interview.
   Before he left for the Thanksgiving holiday last week, Bush named
retired Air Force Gen. Brent Scowcroft as his national security
adviser. There is some thinking that Bush may keep CIA Director
William Webster on the job in an interim appointment.
   Once he fixes his national security team, Bush is likely to set
his sights on two other big agencies, Commerce and HHS, according to
one source close to the transition. The source spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Bush's aides have said there is no set timetable for having a
government in place. ``We have about 60 days between now and
inauguration and I think the vice president is wise to use as much
of that clock to his own benefit,'' Sununu said.
   At Commerce, Robert Mosbacher, a Houston oilman and Bush's old
friend, is thought to have the edge over the other candidates. If
both he and Tower are picked, Bush would have at least four Texans
in high-ranking jobs. Others are James A. Baker III, the designated
secretary of state and Lauro Cavazos, the education secretary.
   Here is the scuttlebutt on some other agencies.
   _ HHS. Rep. Willis D. Gradison Jr., R-Ohio, has emerged as a
leading candidate to head the huge federal agency that runs the
costly Medicare and Medicaid health insurance programs as well as
Social Security, the Food and Drug Administration and the National
Institutes of Health.
   Gradison, a classmate of Bush's at Yale, is ranking Republican on
the Ways and Means health subcommittee that deals with Medicare, an
$80 billion program expected to expand at more than double the rate
of overall inflation over the next few years without spending cuts.
   Another serious candidate is Monroe Trout, who runs a chain of
non-profit hospitals in California and serves with Barbara Bush on
the board of directors of Morehouse College, a black institution in
Atlanta. A physician and lawyer, he headed a major pharmaceutical
company and was active in Republican politics in Connecticut before
moving to California and has been in Washington this month talking
with various people about his interest in the job.
   Among other names bandied about the the job are Rep. Lynn Martin,
R-Ill, Surgeon General C. Everett Koop and Dorcas Hardy, the Social
Security commissioner.
   _ Labor. A name that has been given serious attention recently is
that of Constance Horner, head of the Office of Personnel
Management. Martin is another candidate for this job, as is Rep.
Thomas Ridge, R-Pa.
   _ Energy. Former Rep. Henson Moore of Louisiana says he is under
consideration for this job. ``From the best we can tell, it's
getting serious,'' he said in an interview. Another possible
candidate if Frederick Khedouri, a former aide to Bush. Sen. James
McClure, a Republican on the Energy and Natural Resources Committee,
is publicly backing Peter Johnson, a former administrator at the
Bonneville Power Administration, for the job.
   _ Interior. The talk is that Sen. Dan Evans, R-Wash., who is
retiring from the Senate at the end of the year, is still in the
running for this position. Others are Rep. Dick Cheney, R-Wyo.,
William Ruckelhaus, former head of the Environmental Protection
Agency, and Nathaniel Reed, a former assistant secretary.
   _ Transportation. Besides Fuller, others who might fit the bill
are Gov. Thomas Kean of New Jersey and Rep. Guy Molinari, R-N.Y.
   While jockeying continues at other places, such as the
agriculture department and the EPA, no front-runners seem to have
emerged.
</TEXT>
