<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0525 11-26 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0525,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Protectionism Must Be Rejected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, Reagan used, to show election was last week.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan urged Americans on
Saturday to reject ``the siren song'' of trade protectionism and
vowed to push in December for greater U.S. access to overseas
markets.
   In his last nationally broadcast radio address from the
presidential ranch in the Santa Ynez Mountains near here, Reagan
pledged to have U.S. trade negotiators fight in Montreal next month
for more protection for U.S. intellectual property rights,
investments and trade in services, as well as goods.
   The president was referring to a mid-term review of the so-called
Uruguay Round of negotiations under the auspices of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, a multilateral pact in which the
United States and some 95 other countries meet and discuss problems
sin the field of international trade and competition.
   Reagan used Saturday's adddres to again hail the election victory
of Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney early last week, saying
the voters of Canada sent a message to the world rejecting
protectionist sentiment.
   In this country, he said, the multimillion-dollar trade deficits
of recent years had ``led some misguided politicians to call for
protectionism, warning that, otherwise, we would lose jobs. But they
were wrong again. In fact, the United States not only didn't lose
jobs, we created more jobs than all the countries of Western Europe,
Canada and Japan combined.
   ``We too often talk about trade while using the vocabulary of
war. In war, for one side to win, the other must lose,'' he said.
``But commerce is not warfare. Trade is an economic alliance that
benefits both countries. There are no losers, only winners.''
   Reagan argued that ``today, protectionism is being used by some
American politicians as a cheap form of nationalism. ... Our
peaceful trading partners are not our enemies. They are our allies.
We should be beware of the demigogues who are ready to declare a
trade war against our friends.''
   He said the expansion of the international economy ``is not a
foreign invasion. It is an American triumph.''
   Reagan said that when the multilateral trade talks open Dec. 5 in
Montreal, ``we will be in the forefront of efforts to improve this
system.''
   ``We want to open more markets for our markets, to see to it that
all nations play by the rules, and to seek improvement in such areas
as dispute resolution and agriculture,'' he said.
   ``Our negotiators will be working hard for all of us,'' the
president promised.
   Reagan, as he has in the past, raised the ghost of the
Smoot-Hawley Act of 1930, a tariff law which he said had led to the
Great Depression, in which one out of four Americans lost their jobs.
   ``Ever since that time, Americans have stayed true to our
heritage by rejecting the siren song of protectionism,'' Reagan said.
   The five-minute radio address, broadcast from a make-shift studio
step up in a house-trailer on Reagan's 688-acre property, was
Reagan's last from the ranch.
   The president concludes a six-day vacation Sunday and flies back
to Washington. No more visits are scheduled to Rancho del Cielo
before Reagan's term ends on Jan. 20, although the president and his
wife, Nancy, will spend about 10 days around Christmas and New
Year's Day attending parties and visiting friends in Los Angeles and
Palm Springs, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881126-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 1404EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-DemocratsText     11-26 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Democrats Text,770</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democrats' response to
President Reagan's weekly radio address, given by Rep. William H.
Gray III of Pennsylvania:
   Thanksgiving is a uniquely American holiday when we make a point
of giving thanks to the Lord for our material blessings. President
Reagan is understandably proud of the way that much of the American
economy has performed in this sixth year of continued growth.
   The president has spoken about international trade and the need
to avoid protectionism. All of us agree that protectionism is not
the answer to our trade deficit. We need open trade, but we also
need fair trade and a level playing field. Our international balance
_ which turned from a surplus in 1980 to a huge $154 billion deficit
last year _ illustrates how we can misuse our bountiful resources
with the wrong policies. The trade deficit has destroyed jobs and
eroded our industrial base. But the trade deficit fundamentally
means that we spend more than we produce, and that basic imbalance
results from the budget deficit.
   Everyone knows that it is now time to deal with the budget
deficit. The plunge of the dollar and the tremors in the financial
markets right after the election gave a clear signal. The world is
waiting impatiently for U.S. leadership.
   The nation and President-elect Bush now have a unique and
unprecedented opportunity. For the first time in 132 years we have a
vice president moving up to become president. We have a continuity
of administration, already reflected in Mr. Bush's reappointment of
some of President Reagan's most important Cabinet officers. In some
areas Mr. Bush is actively governing. He has met with major foreign
leaders and with the speaker of the House.
   President-elect Bush and President Reagan can take advantage of
this unique opportunity to push the nation rapidly towards a fiscal
solution. All they need to do is have Mr. Bush resent his budget
program when the president's budget is submitted to the Congress, as
required by law, in January. That is what the nation and the world
are waiting for _ the new president's vision and program, which is
the essential basis for budget deliberations and action by the
Congress.
   I am therefore asking President Reagan and President-elect Bush
to join together and begin work now on a budget embodying Mr. Bush's
program, to be presented to Congress in January. To accomplish this,
President Reagan should make available the resources of the Office
of Management and Budget to President-elect Bush, his OMB
Director-designate Mr. Darman, and his transition team.
   This would be the single most effective way to reassure the
nation and the world that we are on a responsible fiscal course.
Democrats in Congress want to join the new administration in solving
the deficit problem and solving it quickly. This year we passed all
the budget legislation before the beginning of the fiscal year. If
we push ahead now, we can do the same next year.
   Mr. Bush told the American people during the election campaign
that he had a plan to reduce the deficit. It was called a ``flexible
freeze.'' He said ti would reduce the deficit without raising taxes,
protect social security, provide the resources for a sound defense,
and allow increased funding for education, protection of the
environment, and other vital national priorities. These are all
admirable goals. If they are mutually attainable, they will have
great appeal and support in Congress. That's why the Reagan-Bush
budget should be ready in January, not sometime much later in the
spring.
   Lately there have been disturbing reports in the press that
President-elect Bush is being advised not to present a budget plan
that shows his own vision and program, but instead to sit down and
negotiate with Congress without a plan. I hope that these reports
are wrong. A failure to present a fiscal plan for the nation would
be a terrible mistake. It would send the wrong signal to the
financial markets _ that we will continue to delay rather than to
act. It would send the wrong signal to the Congress _ that a new
administration will not be responsible and accountable for its
policies. that is the road to dissension and stalemate, not to a
solution.
   It is essential to move ahead now to solve the budget problem, to
bring the trade deficit down, and to solidify our economic future.
The American people, the new Congress and the world are waiting for
some good, old-fashioned leadership and vision. The opportunity is
here, and the time is now.
</TEXT>
