<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     11-26 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former ``Adam 12'' stars Martin Milner
and Kent McCord aim to become television partners again, playing
1980s cops in a tentative new cable TV production, ``Nashville
Beat.''
   The 26 half-hour episodes under consideration would feature
Milner as Nashville's old-fashioned chief of detectives and McCord
as a hip, undercover cop from Los Angeles who has been recruited to
Nashville by Milner, said Michael Marcovsky, chairman of NAC
Productions.
   ``This series will be filmed entirely on location in Nashville
and will reflect the energy and excitement of the city's legendary
country and rock music scene,'' Marcovsky said Friday.
   NAC plans to produce the series with Buck Productions, headed by
McCord. Production hinges on negotiations with cable networks to
schedule the series, which would open with a two-hour movie,
Marcovsky said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish opera tenor Jose Carreras says his charity
concert at the Vatican will be part of a continuing struggle against
leukemia, the disease that struck him last year.
   All proceeds from the Dec. 9 concert will be donated to the
Italian Association Against Leukemia and will go toward building
hospitality centers in Italy for families of leukemia patients, said
Gian Franco Imperatori, chairman of the association.
   Organizers did not say how much they expect to raise from the
concert, which will feature the South American Creole Mass, a
combination of Argentine composer Ariel Ramirez's melodies and
traditional Argentine and Hispanic-American regional songs.
   ``I thought in this spirit of the year, in December, that to do a
Mass is very appropriate,'' Carreras said at a news conference
Friday. ``Of course I am doing it in Rome for obvious reasons _ the
head office of the Italian Association Against Leukemia is here and
Italy is a place I consider my second country. And to do a Mass in
Rome, it has to be at the Vatican.''
   Carreras, 42, has become an internationally renowned operatic
tenor since his debut in 1970.
   He was treated last year in Spain and the United States for
leukemia, and his doctors said he no longer has symptoms of the
disease, according to a spokeswoman.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A post-wedding gift for hockey star Wayne Gretzky
_ a stick once used by the legendary Gordie Howe _ was stolen
shortly before its intended delivery.
   Dr. Murray Howe, Gordie Howe's son, planned to give Gretzky the
hockey stick after the Los Angeles Kings of the National Hockey
League played the Detroit Red Wings here Wednesday.
   ``I took so many precautions to hand-deliver it so it wouldn't
get lost in the mail or something like that. It was one of my dad's
old sticks that he used in the playoffs during the 1950s,'' said
Howe, who played with Gretzky when they were teens in the mid-1970s.
   ``I didn't know how much Janet would appreciate it, but I knew
Wayne would,'' he said. ``My dad was Wayne's idol, so I thought I
would bring it ... and surprise him with it.''
   As Howe watched the Kings defeat Detroit 8-3, the stick was at
his feet. But when the game ended, it was gone.
   ``My feet were right on top of it. I don't know how they got
it,'' Howe said.
   Gretzky, former star of the Edmonton Oilers, married actress
Janet Jones in August. He was traded to the Kings later that month.
 
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Walters, whose 50th television special
will feature a compilation of interviews from a dozen years of her
programs, says she's never delved into sensationalism.
   ``Nobody sits and describes their perversions,'' she said of her
specials in a recent interview. ``In all our interviews over 12
years, there isn't one that's prurient.''
   The 50th show, to be broadcast Tuesday, will feature interviews
with personalities ranging from the Shah of Iran to Cher.
   With flying chairs, fisticuffs, shouting and discussion of
unusual sexual practices appearing on talk shows, Walters was asked
her opinion of other interviewers.
   She said ``The Morton Downey Jr. Show,'' on which verbal and
sometimes physical sparring is common, is entertaining but not a
show she would watch every week ``because I really don't believe
it.''
   Walters said she hasn't seen ``Geraldo,'' though she worked with
its host, Geraldo Rivera, on ABC's ``20@20.'' ``I only saw the
clips of it when the chair hit him in the nose,'' she said,
referring to the highly publicized melee that erupted earlier this
month during a show on white supremacists.
   Walters said she believes both Phil Donahue's ``Donahue'' and
Oprah Winfrey's ``Oprah'' are trying to compete with the sometimes
sensational content of ``Geraldo.''
   ``In a way, that's unfortunate,'' she said.
</TEXT>
