<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LottoImmigrant     11-26 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lotto Immigrant,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winner Of $14.3 Million Lottery Moved To U.S. In Search Of Riches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 23-year-old man who moved to the
United States from Turkey seven months ago in search of riches found
them last week when he won $14.3 million in the California Lottery.
   ``I told my family I would be a millionaire by the age of 25,''
said Zafer Altintas. ``I didn't think I would win the millions. I
thought I would have to earn it myself.''
   Altintas made his fortune with a $3 investment, buying three
tickets in Wednesday's ``Lotto 6-49'' game and picking all six
winning numbers on one of the tickets. One of the winning numbers,
39, was picked by mistake; Altintas said he meant to mark 38 on the
card.
   Since learning he will be a millionaire, Altintas quit his
$6.50-an-hour job as a hotel housekeeper, treated his friends to a
champagne brunch and bought a new car.
   ``I was planning to buy the car anyway, but I was just waiting
until March to get my income tax return to make the down payment,''
he said. ``I went there and the salesman recognized me from
television, and they gave me the car.''
   He said he plans to use some of his winnings, which will be paid
in 20 annual installments, to build a luxury hotel on Turkey's west
coast, buy a home for himself, another for his mother in Istanbul
and a car for his brother.
   Altintas, an American citizen, was born in St. Louis but reared
in Turkey.
</TEXT>
