<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DepartingSenators 1stLd-Writethru a0519 11-26 1240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Departing Senators, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Of Eleven Departing Senators Doing So By Choice</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 23rd graf, ``Sen. Daniel Quayle xxx'' to CORRECT party
affiliation</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One hundred and sixty-three years of collective
experience will be missing from the Senate floor when the 101st
Congress convenes in January.
   Seven senators are departing by their own choice, including the
one elected vice president who gives up his seat and vote on the
floor to move to the status of presiding officer.
   Four were shown the door by voters.
   The departures will force a reshuffling of several key positions
inside the 200-year old lawmaking body, including the chairmanships
of its Appropriations, Budget and Banking committees. All are
important players in a year in which the federal budget deficit is
expected to dominate legislative scorecards.
   Six of those leaving the Senate have served a dozen or more years.
   The list includes the Senate's oldest and most senior member,
Sen. John Stennis, D-Miss., 87, who, after 41 years of service, is
perhaps the chamber's most revered member.
   Stennis, who for years had pledged to ``plough my row to the
end,'' is leaving somewhat reluctantly, his decision spurred by his
advanced age and uncertain health. He was severely wounded in a
robbery attempt in 1973 and has been confined to a wheelchair since
he lost a leg to cancer several years ago.
   The senator's departure opens up the chairmanship of the Senate
Appropriations Committee as well as the position of president pro
tempore, the Senate's highest constitutional office.
   Under the law, Stennis was third in line of succession to the
presidency, following the vice president and the Speaker of the
House.
   Stennis almost certainly will be replaced both in the
Appropriations chairmanship and as president pro tem by Sen. Robert
C. Byrd, D-W.Va., who is stepping down as Senate majority leader.
   Another retiree, Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., 73, is ending a
31-year career that began when he won a special 1957 election to
succeed the controversial Sen. Joseph R. McCarthy.
   Proxmire missed only 18 roll call votes in his more than three
decades of service and none in the last 22 years. He cast 10,261
consecutive votes from April 1966 until the 100th Congress adjourned
last month. A total 12,152 roll calls were taken in the Senate since
Proxmire arrived in 1957. Proxmire was present and voting for 99.85
percent of them.
   He delivered more than 3,300 consecutive daily speeches on the
U.S. failure to ratify the 1948 treaty making genocide a crime and
persisted until the Senate ratified the pace and passed implementing
legislation making genocide a crime under U.S. law.
   For this, Proxmire was hailed by B'Nai B'rith as one whose name
``will be forever enshrined in the Pantheon of heroes who have
fought so gallantly on behalf of man's humanity to man.''
   Proxmire is perhaps best known by the public at large as father
of the monthly ``Golden Fleece'' awards which, since March of 1975,
targeted Proxmire's choices for ``the biggest example of ridiculous,
ironic or wasteful spending.''
   One example: a federal grant for a study of why prisoners want to
escape from jail.
   He has announced that the award of the Golden Fleece will
continue after his Senate tenure ends. He will continue to issue it
as a member of the board of directors of the National Taxpayers
Union.
   Proxmire was chairman of the Senate Banking Committee and
responsible for significant legislation in the field. He was a
senior member of the Appropriations Committee. He often called being
a member of the Senate ``the best job in the country, bar none,''
better even than being president.
   While Stennis and Proxmire went to the sidelines voluntarily,
Sen. Lowell Weicker, R-Conn., was shoved there by Connecticut's
voters, losing a tight race to state Atty. Gen. Joseph Lieberman.
   Weicker, heir to a Squibb pharmaceutical fortune, was the
Senate's most liberal and independent Republican, an outspoken
advocate who loudly and vigorously opposed the social agenda of
conservatives.
   He gained national attention in 1973 as a member of the Senate
Watergate Committee which he used as a forum to denounce the
activities of President Nixon and his staff.
   Also ending careers as senators this year are:
   _Sen. Daniel Quayle, R-Ind., 41, who, by virtue of his election
to the vice presidency, will become president of the Senate and,
when he chooses, preside over its deliberations. But he can only
vote to break a tie. Quayle's selection as George Bush's vice
presidential running mate touched off a storm of criticism over his
alleged lack of credentials to succeed to the nation's highest
office and his alleged use of family influence to win him a place in
the Indiana National Guard, thus avoiding combat service in Vietnam.
Quayle was elected to the Senate in 1980.
   _Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., 58, chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee, and a major figure in the congressional battles over the
massive federal budget deficit. Chiles first won election in 1970
after walking his state and earning the nickname, ``Walkin'
Lawton.'' Chiles was heavily favored to win re-election and his
decision to skip the race was a surprise. He said he had lost his
enthusiasm for the job. ``At some stage, maybe there is a burnout,''
he said.
   _Sen. Daniel Evans, R-Wash., 58, a 12-year governor of Washington
was appointed to his seat after the death of Sen. Henry Jackson,
D-Wash., in September 1983. Evans, a member of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, also expressed frustration with the job,
complaining of a lack of substantive debate and said the Senate's
eratic schedule had often denied him a personal life.
   _Sen. Robert T. Stafford, R-Vt., 75, a former Vermont governor,
was a member of the House when he was appointed in 1971 to fill the
unexpired term of Sen. Winston Prouty, D-Vt., who had died. He had
previously served as a prosecutor, state attorney general and
lieutenant governor. His Senate career focused on the environment
and education.
   _Paul Trible, R-Va., 42, said he was quitting the Senate after
one term because he wanted to spend more time with his family. He is
widely expected to become a candidate for governor of Virginia. In
the Senate, Trible was a member of the Senate Iran-Contra
investigating committee and compiled a conservative voting record.
   _John Melcher, D-Mont., 64, by profession a veternarian, lost the
Senate seat he had held since 1976 in an upset to Republican Conrad
Burns, a farm broadcaster. In the Senate, Melcher concentrated on
farm issues. During the Iran-Contra affair he complained about those
who described members of the National Security Council staff as
freewheeling ``White House cowboys.'' That was demeaning to cowboys,
Melcher said.
   _Chic Hecht, R-Nev., 59, a conservative clothing store owner who
was almost invisible in the Senate, was beaten in his bid for a
second term by Democratic Gov. Richard Bryan. Hecht was known for
slips of the tongue and once refered to a proposed nuclear dump site
in his state as a ``nuclear supository.''
   _David K. Karnes, R-Neb., at 39 the youngest of the departing
senators, was appointed to his seat in March 1987 to fill the
vacancy created by the death of Sen. Edward Zorinsky, a Democrat. He
was defeated by former Democratic Gov. Robert Kerrey after a
campaign in which Karnes, in a major gaffe, told his Farm Belt
voters that ``we need fewer farmers.''
</TEXT>
