<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Kristallnacht-Vandalism     11-26 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kristallnacht-Vandalism,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspects Arrested, Arraigned In Cemetery Vandalism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOONSOCKET, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four men have been arrested in connection
with the vandalism of a 98-year-old Jewish cemetery and police
officers are giving varying accounts of what their motivation might
have been.
   Swastikas and anti-Jewish slurs were discovered at the B'nai
Israel Cemetery on Nov. 8, the day before the 50th anniversary of
Kristallnacht, the night of Nazi violence against Jews across
Germany that marked the start of the Nazi Holocaust. Germans called
it ``crystal night'' because of all the windows broken from Jewish
businesses and synagogues.
   Police have not officially determined if the desecration of about
a half-dozen tombstones and the entrance road was related to
Kristallnacht or an act of satanic worship, Sgt. Richard Flood said
Friday.
   But Lt. Gordon D. Tempest told The Woonsocket Call that police
believe as many as five individuals were involved in the attack as
part of a satanic-like cult.
   ``We've had conflicting reports, but we do believe that it is (a
cult),'' Tempest said. Tempest gave no details on what might suggest
cult involvement.
   The attorney general's office will review the case on Dec. 5,
said Sgt. Mario Andreoni.
   Police said they didn't believe the vandalism was connected to a
similar act at the Precious Blood Cemetery, a Roman Catholic
graveyard, which was discovered Nov. 18.
   Police arrested Steven S. Coutcher, 18, of Woonsocket, on
Wednesday and Bertrand C. Cabana, 23, of Providence, on Friday,
Flood said. Later Friday, George M. Neves, 19, of Central Falls, and
Thomas P. Elefsiades Jr., 18, of Pawtucket, were arrested, police
said.
   Coutcher admitted to his role in the vandalism and implicated two
others, said Detective William J. Shea.
   All four were charged with vandalism and desecration of a
cemetery and have been arraigned, police said. Two were released on
bail Friday and the other two on Saturday.
   If convicted, they face up to five years in jail and fines of up
to $10,000.
</TEXT>
