<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Quake     11-26 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Quake,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worst Quake In Half Century Shakes Parts of Canada And U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>By SOLL SUSSMAN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Canada's strongest earthquake in 53 years,
which caused minor damage and no serious injuries, produced banner
headlines Saturday, from ``All Quebec Trembles'' to ``Shake, Rattle
'n Roll.''
   The jolt in Montreal disrupted the filming of a syndicated
television show during an earthquake scene and in Toronto, and a man
blamed his strange sensations on too much drinking.
   The earthquake at 6:48 p.m. EST Friday lasted more than two
minutes and measured 6 on the Richter scale, said John Adams of the
Ottawa-based Geological Survey of Canada. Its epicenter was in
Quebec's Charlevoix region, about 95 miles north of Quebec City, he
said.
   The quake cut power and telephone lines in some cities and shook
buildings from Nova Scotia on the Atlantic coast to the western
Ontario city of Sault Ste. Marie. The tremor was felt in the
northeastern United States from Michigan to Washington, D.C.
   ``This is the largest earthquake in Eastern Canada since 1935,''
Adams said.
   The quake buckled railroad tracks, triggered burglar alarms and
swept objects from tables and shelves throughout the affected area.
   The Canadian Press news agency reported that about 50 people were
treated for cuts and bruises or shock in Chicoutimi, about 90 miles
northwest of Quebec City.
   Publicist Jonathan Holiff of ``Starting from Scratch,'' a
syndicated comedy starring Connie Stevens and Bill Daly, told The
Gazette of Montreal that several props were set up to fall during
the show's earthquake scene, ``but a few more things fell off the
wall than were expected.''
   The show is being filmed at Tele-Metropole studios in Montreal.
   The Montreal newspaper Le Devoir, which headlined, ``All Quebec
Trembles,'' added, ``The Earthquake Sows Fear but Causes Nothing
More than Light Damage.''
   The tabloid Toronto Sun headlined ``Earthquake!'' and the
Montreal Daily News said ``Shake, Rattle 'n Roll.''
   ``I just thought I was drinking too much,'' Charles Miles, a
66-year-old downtown Toronto resident told the Toronto Star. ``The
landlord was fixing my sink but he didn't notice anything. That's
why I called (the newspaper) to find out if it was me or an
earthquake.''
   In the United States, where there were no reports of damage,
maitre d' Stephen Brown of Boston's Top of the Hub restaurant on the
52nd floor of the Prudential Center said 120 people were dining at
the time of the tremor.
   ``The entire dining room felt it. Everyone felt they were
becoming dizzy or faint. They all sort of smiled and looked at each
other,'' he said.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said he was in the Executive Mansion in
Albany when ``the chandelier shook. The floor moved. It lasted about
10 seconds but it was something I'll remember for much longer than
that.''
   Canadian Press said the most severe power outages, which lasted
up to an hour, affected 250,000 people in the city of Quebec and
50,000 in Montreal. Quebec City police said a pedestrian was hit and
killed by a car in an intersection during the blackout.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. An earthquake measuring 5 on the Richter scale can
cause considerable damage, a 6 reading severe damage, and a 7 is a
major earthquake.
   The strongest earthquake in Canada this century was recorded off
the coast of British Columbia in 1949 and measured 8 on the Richter
scale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
