<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bush     11-26 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Fish For Bush, No Answers For Reporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush went fishing Saturday,
but he had no more luck hooking trout than reporters had in getting
him to bite on questions about upcoming Cabinet appointments.
   ``Hey, look, you guys, you're scaring the fish away. There aren't
any here anyway. The more you talk, the further away they go,'' Bush
said as he fished for in the nearby Kennebunk River.
   However, Bush told reporters he would turn his attention to
defense appointments and defense policy next week in Washington.
   Bush will also meet on Monday with Senate Republican Leader Bob
Dole, according to aide Stephen Hart.
   Bush and his onetime rival for the Republican presidential
nomination had wanted to meet for some time, Hart said.
   ``It's of mutual interest,'' he added.
   Hart said Bush has yet to make a decision on either defense
policy or on naming a secretary of defense.
   Commenting on a story in Saturday's editions of the Washington
Post that Bush would consider a wide array of possible defense cuts
next week, Hart said:
   ``During the transition process, the vice president is welcoming
discussion on a wide variety on policy considerations and on people.
   ``Simply because options are being given to him and being
discussed and raised, doesn't mean they're going to be accepted.''
   The story also said former Armed Services Chairman John Tower of
Texas remains the front-runner for the job, and that Bush had
decided to keep on CIA Director William Webster, at least for the
time being.
   Bush worked for several hours in the small cottage he uses as an
office on the grounds of his family compound here, then went fishing
with two old friends.
   Asked by reporters what he was fishing for, Bush said, ``basic
brown trout.'' However, he added, ``We usually catch nothing right
here, nothing at all.''
   Why then, he was asked, was he fishing?
   ``Because I like casting,'' the vice president replied.
   Asked if he had thought about his defense team, Bush said: ``I'm
thinking mainly about fishing. Haven't gotten into the defense team
up here. Will as soon as we get back, though.'' Asked specifically
about whether he will name former Sen. John Tower to the post, Bush
said, ``hey gang, c'mon,'' then warned about scaring away the fish.
   Bush fished for about half an hour.
   Hart, meanwhile, told reporters that Robert Teeter, co-director
of Bush's transition team, would not announce his decision until
after Dec. 1 on whether he will accept an offer to be deputy White
House chief of staff.
   The offer was disclosed by New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, who
will be Bush's staff chief.
   Hart said that Bush has no plans to meet with either Teeter or
Sununu during his vacation here; nor had he spoken to Tower.
</TEXT>
