<DOCNO> AP881126-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 1607EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Algeria     11-26 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Algeria,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Of Ruling Party To Consider Major Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Chadli Bendjedid's moves to
loosen his ruling party's grip on the country and avoid further
unrest face opposition in the army and political elite as the party
congress begins Sunday.
   The 5,000 delegates to the sixth National Liberation Front
congress, in addition to considering reform, will choose a
secretary-general during the two-day meeting.
   Bendjedid proposed reform after rising prices, unemployment and
food shortages sparked riots in October that by official count
killed 176 people. Unofficial reports put the figure at up to 500.
   The president wants to revamp the party by bringing in new and
younger faces, a party source said. He wants to get a solid majority
behind his new premier, Kasdi Merbah, and begin revitalizing the
economy.
   Algeria faces a $23 billion foreign debt, a 22 percent
unemployment rate and shrinking oil revenues due to a world oil glut.
   But Bendjedid is faced with opposition from an old guard
comfortable with the monopoly of power built up over the 26 years
since independence from France.
   The source, a party Central Committee member close to Bendjedid,
said the president will have to slow down proposed reforms to win
agreement to the changes. The sources spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   A move toward a multiparty democracy, discussed a month ago,
seems on a back burner. The political program says the front ``does
not exclude that political action developed at grassroots level
could lead eventually to political pluralism.''
   But the Central Committee source, and many other observers, agree
that a multiparty system is not coming in the near future.
   According to the constitution, the secretary-general, now
Bendjedid, becomes the sole candidate in the presidential elections.
The elections are scheduled for February.
   Bendjedid has not announced whether he will seek a third
five-year term, but he is widely expected to.
   Bendjedid's speech Oct. 10 promising the reforms has led to
heightened expectations among many Algerians and the question most
asked by political observers is whether the president will deliver
enough change fast enough to avert new riots.
   The exact form the changes will take is not clear. The reform
program, as published in the official press, is more of a
philosophical statement than a concrete plan of action.
   The National Liberation Front began as a military organization
leading the revolution that began Nov. 1, 1954 and emerged as a
party in the late 1970s.
   Bendjedid, a military man, tried to minimize the role of the army
and has been trying since 1985 to overcome resistance to
liberalization.
   Since the riots, the president has appointed Merbah and a new
government of technocrats, removed the No. 2 man in the party and
made changes in the top army command.
   On Nov. 3, voters approved a referendum that changed 14 articles
of the constitution. One measure granted wider powers to the premier
and making him directly responsible to the National Assembly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
