<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-CostaRica     11-26 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Costa Rica,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Costa Rica, Nicaragua Sign Border Patrol Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has signed an agreement
with Costa Rica to set up border patrols and to return several
hundred refugees to Nicaragua, officials announced.
   According to an official statement, the agreement commits both
governments to patrol the border in order to ``guarantee frontier
normality, prevent unlawful acts such as smuggling and cattle
rustling ... and fight drug trafficking.''
   The accords were signed Thursday in the Nicaraguan port of San
Juan del Sur, officials said in Managua Friday.
   Costa Rican and Nicaraguan troops will patrol separately, said
Hernan Garron, Costa Rica's minister of public security.
   Tomas Borge, Nicaragua's interior minister, said Costa Rica
``reaffirmed its neutrality with all that that implies.''
   Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government has frequently accused
Costa Rica of harboring anti-Sandinista guerrillas, known as Contras.
   The U.S.-backed rebels have been fighting the leftist government
for seven years. A temporary cease-fire remains in effect, but each
side accuses the other of violating it and progress on a permanent
truce has been stalled.
   Radio Liberation, a clandestine radio station operated by
anti-Sandinista guerrillas, denounced the border agreement on
Friday, calling it a ``crime against the people of Nicaragua.''
   Costa Rican patrols will try to locate Radio Liberation's
broadcast facilities, which Nicaragua says are in Costa Rica,
according to Costa Rican police minister Antonio Alvarez.
   Several hundred refugees who fled Nicaragua after Hurricane Joan
hit last month will be repatriated under the agreement, officials
said.
</TEXT>
