<HEAD>Pope To Visit East Germany In 1991, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II plans to visit
communist East Germany in 1991, a West German newspaper said
Saturday.
   There was no official confirmation from the Vatican on the report
in the paper Welt am Sonntag.
   The conservative newspaper, quoting unidentified Roman Catholic
Church officials in the East German city of Dresden, said the pope
is to visit the East bloc country for the first time in May 1991.
   Details of the pope's visit were worked out by Berlin Cardinal
Joachim Meisner and East German Secretary of State Kurt Loeffler,
who is responsible for church affairs.
   The focal point of the trip would be the beatification of
Bernhard Lichtenberg, a Roman Catholic priest who died in November
1943 while being transported to the Nazi death camp of Dachau, now
in southern West Germany, Welt am Sonntag said.
   Lichtenberg was arrested in 1941 because of his open opposition
to the Nazi persecution of Jews.
</TEXT>
