<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SoakedTwine     11-26 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soaked Twine,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>12,000 Tons Of Baling Twine Ruined</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 4 billion feet of baling twine _ enough
to encircle Earth more than 95 times and worth as much as $6 million
_ was ruined after the ship transporting it took on water during a
North Atlantic storm.
   The 12,000 tons of sisal twine was bound for Duluth and then to
upper Midwest farmers to tie bales of hay, an executive said. It was
aboard a Greek-owned ship carrying the load from Brazil when the
storm struck Thursday.
   ``It's a tremendous loss to us,'' said Joseph Urista, director
and part owner of United Rope Distributors of Minneapolis. The
company is a subsidiary of Sisalana Inc., a Brazilian company that
makes twine from sisal, a tropical fiber.
   Urista said the twine was valued at $5 million to $6 million. It
was insured, but he said his company will have to buy replacement
twine from competitors and increase its own production in order to
meet the Midwestern farm demand.
   The 316,000 bales of twine could have tied 79 million small bales
of hay and well over 11 million large ones, he said.
   The ship's 27 Filipino crewmen and East Indian officers were
rescued by a Canadian Coast Guard helicopter about 400 miles south
of Sable Island, an island off Nova Scotia. None was injured.
   The rescue took place in 25- to 35-knot winds and 22-foot seas as
the remains of Tropical Storm Keith approached the area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
