<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Denver     11-26 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Denver,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Starts Fund To Pay For One-Way Trip to Space for Singer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYNE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pillow salesman wants to help singer John
Denver pay for a trip into outer space. But Lyle George has only a
one-way ticket in mind.
   George said his goal is to raise $5 million, or half the $10
million Denver has said he would need to spend one week aboard the
Soviet space station Mir.
   Denver, who approached the Soviets about a space trip, has said
it would be inappropriate for him personally to pay the Soviet space
program. The singer said he hoped individual and corporate
sponsorships will enable him to go into space by December 1989.
   George decided to respond by opening the fund at State National
Bank in Wayne, which is 90 miles northwest of Omaha. He donated $10
and said he's received some pledges.
   ``I thought it was kind of bizarre when he wanted people to chip
in,'' George said. ``But I decided I'd be willing to chip in if I
could be guaranteed that none of the money would be spent to bring
him back.''
   George said he's not worried about how Denver would return to
Earth.
   ``If he finds a way back, more power to him,'' said George,
adding that he once was a John Denver fan.
   ``My first album was a John Denver album ...,'' George said.
``The first song I listened to on the radio that I remember was
`Rocky Mountain High.' But I feel John Denver has drifted off of
that since then.''
</TEXT>
