<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 1749EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-26 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Severe Weather Over The Mississippi Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An area of low pressure and a cold front trailing southward
produced severe weather with tornadoes Saturday over the lower
Mississippi Valley and snow in the upper Mississippi Valley.
   A line of thunderstorms moved from eastern Texas into western
Mississippi during the morning and early afternoon.
   A tornado destroyed at least four houses and damaged an estimated
25 others at Ruleville, Miss., but no serious injuries were
reported, officials said. The twister, reported to be about 100
yards wide, also caused extensive damage to the high school, the
junior high and a service station in the town of about 3,500.
   Another tornado was spawned by a thunderstorm near Mound, La.,
the National Weather Service said.
   Strong thunderstorm wind damaged a church and a store at
Carthage, Texas, the weather service said. Hail as big as golf balls
fell near Fruitvale and Mexia, Texas.
   Rain from the thunderstorms was heavy over the lower Mississippi
Valley and fell on already soaked ground in Arkansas and Louisiana.
Overnight totals included 6.11 inches at Hope, Ark.; 4.94 inches at
Fulta, Ark.; 3.55 inches at Nashville, Ark.; and 3.13 inches at
Plain Dealing, La.
   In the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, 2.41 inches of rain fell at
Barksdale Air Force Base at Shreveport, La.; 1.95 inches fell at
Pine Bluff, Ark.; and 1.81 inches fell at Memphis, Tenn.
   Nearly 3 inches fell in western Tennessee and a flash flood
warning was posted.
   Throughout eastern Texas, rivers were reported at or near flood
stage and many towns reported losing power for several hours.
   Snow fell in the upper Mississippi Valley and eastern parts of
the northern Plains where cold, moist air blew counterclockwise
around the low pressure area.
   Two to 5 inches of snow fell in southwestern Minnesota during the
morning, before the snow moved north. By midday, 6 inches of snow
had fallen at Brainerd and Cross Lake, with 2 to 3 inches at
Minneapolis-St.Paul.
   Two to 5 inches of snow fell in southeastern South Dakota and the
snow was expected to move into southeastern North Dakota. Two to 4
inches of snow fell in northwestern Wisconsin.
   Light snow also fell as far south as the Texas Panhandle.
   In the West, snow showers were scattered over mountainous areas
of the central and northern so-called Intermountain region between
the Rockies and the Sierra Nevada.
   Parts of Utah got heavy snow overnight. The Alta ski area
reported 30 inches of snow from Friday afternoon to Saturday
morning. The Spruces area in Big Cottonwood Canyon reported 18
inches of snow and the Brighton area had 13 inches.
   Temperatures were freezing in the northern and central Rockies,
the northern Plains, northern Minnesota and western Nebraska and
Kansas.
   But Brownsville, Texas, reported a record high of 93 degrees, and
Portland, Maine, tied its record of 58.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 7
degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., to 92 at Brownsville. Saturday morning's
low was 6 degrees below zero at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from the
central and eastern Gulf Coast across the Tennessee and middle
Mississippi valleys, the Ohio Valley and the Appalachians to the
Great Lakes and western New England. Snow was forecast over the
upper Mississippi Valley, western parts of the upper Great Lakes,
and eastern sections of the northern Plains. Widespread rain was
forecast across the Pacific Northwest, with snow at higher
elevations.
   Highs only in the teens and 20s were predicted over the northern
Rockies, northern Plains, Nebraska and much of the upper Mississippi
Valley; in the 30s and 40s from the Pacific Northwest across the
central and southern Rockies, Oklahoma, Kansas and much of the
middle Mississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes; in the 40s over
northern Maine; in the 70s over southern California and parts of the
desert Southwest; in the 70s and 80s from south-central Texas across
the Gulf Coast and Florida to eastern parts of the middle and
southern Atlantic Coast states; and in the 50s and 60s over much of
the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
