<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ChessOlympiad     11-26 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chess Olympiad,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Men, Women Keep Chess Lead in Olympiad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALONICA, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union defeated Denmark 3-1 in
the 12th round of the Chess Olympiad on Saturday to retain their
overwhelming three-point lead with only two rounds left.
   England scored a decisive 3-1 win over Hungary to take strong
hold of second place with 31 points.
   The United States, the Netherlands and Yugoslavia shared third
with 29.5 points.
   The Soviets have 34 points of a possible 48.
   In the separate women's championship, the Soviet Union maintained
its half-point lead over Hungary despite losing an important player
to international romance.
   The Soviets' second board, Elena Akhmilovskaya, eloped Saturday
morning with John Donaldson, the non-playing captain of the American
men's team. They left for the United States.
   The Soviets, forced to field their three remaining players, only
defeated Czechoslovakia 2.5-0.5. But the Hungarians also ceded a
draw in their 2.5-0.5 win over England. A win scores a point, and a
draw earns a half point.
   Although the Soviet men are brilliantly poised to win the gold
medals, they almost suffered a setback against Denmark when Curt
Hansen, a 23-year-old Danish grandmaster, appeared to gain a winning
position against world champion Garri Kasparov.
   ``At one stage, Hansen was totally winning with Kasparov in time
trouble too,'' said Danish International Master Bjarke Kristensen.
``But he went wrong, missed several (chances for) wins, and Kasparov
went on to draw.''
   England, the second seeds and 1986 silver medalists, made a
strong play for second place with impressive wins from Grandmasters
Jonathan Speelman and John Nunn.
   The United States, which has won the bronze medals in the last
three Olympiads, only drew 2-2 with the outranked Netherlands.
   U.S. players seemed tired after most rose early to escort their
eloping captain to the airport.
   Following his departure, the United States appointed a new
captain, Natasha Us, a 26-year-old chess expert from New York.
   The Philippines, seeded 29th but now in sixth place, continued
their remarkable run Saturday by going 1.5-0.5 ahead against China
with two games adjourned. Experts said the match would probably
finish 2.5-1.5 in favor of the Filipinos and push them into third
place.
   Organized by the 127-member World Chess Federation, the Olympiad
is a biennial world team championship featuring teams from 106
countries.
   The adjourned games and the 13th round are scheduled for Sunday.
The final round will be played Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
