<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ToyProtest     11-26 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toy Protest,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activists Demonstrate Against War Toys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magician made toy guns disappear
here Saturday while activists demonstrated at a Rhode Island toy
factory in pre-Christmas protests against violent playthings.
   Jerry Rubin, director of the Los Angeles Alliance for Survival,
said the events were held for the fourth annual International Days
of Protest Against War Toys.
   At a child care center in Santa Monica, Rubin was joined by
magician Charles Peters, who turned Rambo and G.I. Joe dolls into
teddy bears, which he tossed to a small crowd.
   For his finale, Peters made realistic toy guns vanish and two
white doves appear in their place.
   ``I think people can participate in making their own magic this
holiday season and all year round. They can stop buying war toys and
make them disappear from store shelves,'' said Rubin, who has been
involved with Alliance for Survival for nine years and is not
related to the 1960's anti-war activist also named Jerry Rubin.
   In Pawtucket, R.I., a demonstration was held outside Hasbro Inc.,
which makes G.I. Joe, said protest spokeswoman Karen Nyer.
   ``Santa Claus was there telling the kids he wasn't giving out war
toys this year,'' Ms. Nyer said.
   ``We are trying to convince Hasbro to make toys which encourage
and teach cooperation and peace-making skills to our children,''
said Carol Hanley, of the Rhode Island Mobilization for Survival.
   In a radio address, California state Senate leader David Roberti
urged parents not to give violent toys to their children this
holiday season.
   A Roberti bill passed this year by the Legislature bans the
manufacture, sale and distribution of imitation firearms in
California after Dec. 31.
   ``Let's not turn our gifts of love into instruments of death,''
he said.
</TEXT>
