<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Honolulu Mayor,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Undergoes Heart Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Frank F. Fasi underwent a heart bypass
operation on Saturday and is recovering satisfactorily, doctors said.
   Fasi, 68, could be back at work as soon as two weeks, although
``it's too soon to say just how long recovery will take,'' said Dr.
Robert Hong, Fasi's cardiologist.
   Fasi was ``doing fine,'' in the intensive care unit at The
Queen's Medical Center, a hospital spokesman said Saturday.
   Fasi, a Republican, was re-elected Nov. 8 to his fifth four-year
term as mayor of the City-County of Honolulu, which has a population
of about 800,000.
   The mayor experienced ``chest discomfort'' two weeks ago during
exertion, and tests revealed coronary artery blockage, Hong said.
   Fasi otherwise is in good health and no complications are
anticipated, said Dr. Richard Mamiya, who performed the surgery.
