<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AIDSSentence     11-26 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Sentence,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Victim Gets Five Years In Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court sentenced a man to five
years in prison for continuing to have sexual relations after he was
diagnosed as having AIDS, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   The Municipal Court of Prague, hearing the case on appeal, added
an additional two years to the man's original three-year sentence
that was handed down by the court in October, Slobodne Slovo
reported.
   The report said the man tested positive for AIDS in December 1986
and was the first such reported victim of the disease in
Czechoslovakia.
   The daily newspaper said the man continued to have homosexual
relations ``not with one, but with 16 partners (and) did not use
condoms.''
   The 26-year-old student was reported as saying that he failed to
use condoms ``out of fear that he would lose his partners.'' The
report did not say when the verdict was handed down.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   The fatal disease is spread most often through sexual contact,
needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood
products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
