<2ND_LINE>AM-Wedding Replay,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disappointed in the Video, They Replay the Wedding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORQUAY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wedding was a success but the video
was a flop, so Claire Lockett and Michael Narramore reassembled the
cast of hundreds, put their wedding finery back and staged a remake
of the big moment on Saturday.
   Despite five hours of shooting, the videotape of the original
wedding two months ago amounted to only eight usable minutes of
distinctly patchy quality.
   Rita Lockett was so disappointed not to have a video record of
her daughter's big day that she spent $18,500 for a repeat
performance, skipping only the ceremony itself.
   A fleet of limousines took family and friends from the church in
the south coast resort town to the five-star Imperial Hotel for a
glittering reception for 200 guests, just as before.
   Everyone wore exactly the same outfits, sat in precisely the same
positions, and made identical speeches.
   This time they entrusted the filming to an expert and were
counting on a better result.
   There were several TV cameras there as well.
   ``So we will be ending up with the best wedding video of all
time,'' said Mrs. Lockett.
</TEXT>
