<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Hussein     11-26 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Hussein,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hussein Refuses Clemency Petition For Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Saddam Hussein on Saturday refused
to grant clemency for his son, who is accused of killing one of his
father's bodyguards.
   In an address to an Arab youth meeting, Saddam said the case has
been referred to judicial authorities and they would make a decision
in accordance with the law.
   The Iraqi president was responding to a petition submitted by the
meeting's participants seeking a pardon for his 25-year-old son,
Odai, who is under indictment in the Oct. 18 death of Kamel Hana
Gegeo.
   ``I will not make use of my constitutional right to pardon this
man,'' he told the youth meeting.
   ``Rather, if you had asked me to give you my house, I would
immediately collect my belongings and leave,'' he said.
   Other calls for a pardon _ including one from Gegeo's father,
Hana, reportedly a cook for the president _ have appeared in
state-run newspapers over the past few days.
   In a letter published in state-run newspapers earlier this week,
Saddam ordered Justice Minister Akram Abdul Qader Al-Douri to
investigate the killing. Al-Douri appointed a three-member committee
of judges to carry out the investigation.
   His letter said Gegeo was slain during a dispute with Odai as
Gegeo was firing his gun in a villa near the presidential palace.
When Gegeo refused to stop, Odai struck him in the head with a bat.
The letter said Gegeo died in the hospital.
   The Iraqi leader said Odai, the eldest of his five children,
tried to commit suicide after hearing of the death. Informed sources
in Nicosia said the bodyguard was the son of the governess who
raised Saddam's three daughters.
</TEXT>
