<1ST_LINE>r i AM-KillerBees     11-26 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Killer Bees,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Killer Bees Attack Seven in Nicaragua, Stir Fear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A swarm of killer bees apparently
roused by a workman cutting tree branches attacked seven people on
the outskirts of the city, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   A health center treated the victims of the attack Friday for
nausea, dizziness, swelling and pain, but none became seriously ill,
the newspaper Barricada said.
   Callers to a radio talk show of the government's Voice of
Nicaragua criticized Barricada's report, which ran under an
eight-column headline. One of them said it ``could generate hysteria
in the population.''
   An electrical worker cutting tree branches apparently provoked
the attack, the newspaper said.
   Barricada, the newspaper of the ruling Sandinista party, did not
say how it was known that the bees were killer or Africanized bees.
   However, one radio caller said such attacks are frequent in the
countryside, especially in the western part of this Central American
country.
   The bees, descended from South African bees that escaped from a
Brazilian researcher in 1956, are an especially aggressive strain
that produces less honey. In Central and South America, Africanized
bees have largely displaced European bees, which are used for
commercial honeymaking.
   The killer bees have reached southern Mexico and are moving north
at about 200 to 300 miles a year, experts say.
</TEXT>
