<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Libya     11-26 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Libya,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Meets Libyan No. 2; Says He Prays for Gadhafi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II met Saturday with Libya's
second-in-command and said he prays every day for Libyan leader Col.
Moammar Gadhafi.
   The pope met for 30 minutes in his private library with
Staff-Maj. Abdulsalam Jalloud, who is on an official visit to Italy.
The meeting was listed as a private audience and the Vatican
released no details of the talks.
   A Lebanese prelate from the Vatican's Secretariat of State acted
as interpreter for the talks. Afterwards, the pope posed for
photographs with Jalloud and Libya's ambassador to Italy, Abdel
Rahman Shalgam, and presented the Libyans with pontifical medals.
   ``Every day I pray for Libya, especially for President Gadhafi,''
John Paul told his guests. ``Thank you for coming. I bless the
Libyan people.''
   The Libyan official, who arrived a few minutes late, received a
low-key welcome. The pope did not come out of his study to greet him
as he often does with visitors.
   It was the pope's third meeting with Jalloud at the Vatican after
previous visits in May 1982 and December 1984.
   The Holy See does not have formal diplomatic relations with
Libya. But since 1986 the pope has had a representative for Libya
based in Algiers, Archbishop Giovanni De Andrea.
   Jalloud is the highest-ranking Libyan official to make an
official visit to Italy since Libya fired a missile at the tiny
Italian island of Lampedusa in April 1986.
   The missile, which fell harmlessly in the sea, was launched a few
hours after the U.S. bombing raids on two Libyan cities.
   Jalloud met Thursday and Friday with several high-ranking
offficials, including Premier Ciriaco De Mita, President Francesco
Cossiga and Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti.
   His trip is seen as part of a Libyan effort to break out of
international isolation, improve relations with the West and expand
economic ties with European countries.
   Italy, which depends greatly on Libya oil, is Libya's largest
trading partner.
</TEXT>
