<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-TVFugitives     11-26 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-TV Fugitives,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadians Tune In U.S. Television, Nab Criminals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new reality-based crime shows on U.S.
television are reaping some benefits north of the border, where
Canadian viewers have helped police track down at least four
fugitives in less than three months.
   Canadian Press reported Saturday that the latest fugitive to
learn that television signals cross borders was Michael Cooper, 40,
wanted on an Oregon warrant for rape, kidnapping and robbery.
   Cooper had been living in the Vancouver area for more than a year
under an assumed name, CP said.
   Police were tipped off to his whereabouts by a viewer who saw his
picture beamed into Canada by a Tacoma, Wash., television station
showing Fox Broadcasting's syndicated show ``America's Most
Wanted,'' the news agency said.
   A week ago, a man wanted in connection with the rape and murder
of two teen-aged girls in Tennessee was arrested in London, Ontario.
CP said Joseph Shepherd, 35, was detained after a local resident
watched an episode of the NBC's ``Unsolved Mysteries.''
   Shepherd had been on the run since a 1978 shootout with U.S.
marshals, and had been living and working in London under a false
name for at least four years, along with his wife and three
children, Canadian Press said.
   On Sept. 22, ``America's Most Wanted'' chalked up the arrest of
Frederick Merrill. The 41-year-old Connecticut prison escapee and
rape suspect had been living in Toronto but fled to New Brunswick
after a Toronto-area resident recognized him on the program, CP said.
   Two weeks earlier, convicted Philadelphia killer Joseph Kindler
also was recaptured in New Brunswick, it said.
   The subject of a protracted extradition tussle before he escaped
custody in Montreal, Kindler had also been living in Toronto and was
found after a broadcast of America's Most Wanted, the agency said.
   The closest Canadian version of the genre is the Crimestoppers TV
series, which has resulted in more than 14,000 arrests across Canada
since its inception in 1982.
   Typically, ``America's Most Wanted'' screens re-enactments of
particular crimes, together with pertinent details of the fugitives.
Viewers are invited to phone police if they have information.
``Unsolved Mysteries'' follows a similar format.
</TEXT>
