<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 2345EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IRA-Priest     11-26 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IRA-Priest,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Seeks Extradition of Irish Priest for IRA Crimes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain is asking the Republic of Ireland to
extradite a Roman Catholic priest suspected of IRA crimes, police
said Saturday, a day after Belgium freed him to fly home to Dublin.
   Patrick Ryan was freed from a Belgian jail Friday after a
three-week hunger strike in a decision that stirred anger among
British officials.
   In London, legislator Terry Dicks of the governing Conservative
Party said, ``It is ... shameful that the Belgian government should
behave in this way.''
   In the British-ruled province of Northern Ireland, however,
supporters of the outlawed Irish Republican Army cheered the
priest's freedom.
   In Belfast, Gerry Adams, president of the IRA's political wing
known as Sinn Fein, told a rally: ``Father Ryan, like countless
other Irish nationals before him, had been found guilty by the
British media before he had even set foot in an English court. Being
Irish meant he was guilty.''
   Belgian authorities arrested Ryan on June 30 during a raid on a
Brussels apartment. City police were quoted as saying the apartment
contained manuals on bomb-making.
   Ryan was said to have traveled from Spain to Belgium on a false
passport. He initially asked for political asylum in Belgium.
   British authorities initiated moves to extradite Ryan from
Belgium, accusing him of conspiracy to murder and causing bomb
attacks in crimes dating back to 1975.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in mostly Protestant
Northern Ireland and unite it with the Republic of Ireland, which is
95 percent Catholic.
   Belgian Prime Minister Wilfried Martens' government, announcing
its decision to free Ryan, said the facts provided by British
authorities were imprecise and lacked ``the elements of the
punishable offense of gang-forming'' required by Belgian law. He was
flown to Dublin aboard a Belgian military airplane.
   In London on Saturday, police at Scotland Yard headquarters said
magistrates granted a warrant Friday evening for Ryan's extradition.
   Ryan was in Dublin's Blackrock clinic, a hospital, after being
reunited with his family. There was no word on whether his hunger
strike may have damaged his health.
   After Ryan arrived at Dublin airport, Prime Minister Charles
Haughey's socialist government issued a statement referring to
``Father Ryan's right as an Irish citizen to enter this country at
any time.''
   Ryan joined the Catholic Pallotine order in Ireland and became a
priest in 1949. He worked in Tanzania and the United States before
London.
   Britain has tried before to persuade Ireland to extradite
suspects charged with IRA crimes. Irish authorities have repeatedly
refused on technical grounds, creating a sore point in British-Irish
relations.
</TEXT>
