<DOCNO> AP881126-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 2213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TrainDerailment 1stLd-Writethru a0580 11-26 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Derailment, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0580,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Work To Clean Up Derailment That Forced 250 To Evacuate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with higher estimates of spill,
evacuation, cleanup continuing Saturday night, details. Adds byline.
Picks up 10th graf pvs, `The train's....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRUITVALE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities worked Saturday to clean up a
freight train derailment that released a poisonous fertilizer,
forcing the evacuation of more than 250 residents and sending two
motorists to a hospital.
   One witness said the 89-car Union Pacific train might have been
hit by a tornado, causing 35 of its cars to derail. Though a tornado
was reported to have landed in this tiny east Texas town at the
time, authorities said they were uncertain what caused the accident
about 7:30 p.m. Friday during a heavy thunderstorm.
   More than three-quarters of one tank car's 30,000 gallons of
anhydrous ammonia spilled, and the cleanup was continuing 24 hours
later, officials said.
   Anhydrous ammonia is shipped as a liquid, but a puncture would
cause a gas cloud, John Bromley, a spokesman at the railroad's
Omaha, Neb., headquarters, said.
   ``It's a fertilizer, what farmers put on their fields,'' Bromley
said.
   Capt. David Schlottach of the Tyler Fire Department Hazardous
Materials Response Team estimated 6,000 to 7,000 gallons had to be
drained from the car before the cleanup could begin.
   Environmental workers and hazardous waste handlers drained the
ammonia into a pit they dug near the wreckage. There they planned to
neutralize it, pumping in air and then water to create ammonium
hydroxide, which could be vacuumed into storage trucks, Schlottach
said.
   Another car carrying the fertilizer and one carrying chlorine,
which also is hazardous, were not leaking, said Alex Tice, the
railroad's regional director for public relations.
   The train derailed about one-half mile west of the community of
400, which is about 70 miles east of Dallas. Authorities closed two
nearby roads and evacuated residents within one mile to the north
and three-fourths of a mile to the south as a precaution, said
Schlottach.
   The train's four-member crew was not injured, said Tice. However,
two people who were driving near the derailment were overcome by
ammonia fumes and taken to Terrell Community Hospital. An emergency
room supervisor said the two were kept overnight, but were not
seriously injured.
   The Rev. Tom Pesnell said 45 to 50 of the evacuees were staying
at his Main Street Baptist Church in nearby Grand Saline.
   ``There are some that have gone to stay with their various
families. There are some staying in motels,'' he added.
   James Boyd, whose home is about a third of a mile from the
derailment, said what he believed was a tornado ``toppled 15 to 20
cars'' on Highway 80.
   ``It knocked down trees, toppled our TV antenna,'' he said.
   Don Travis, superintendent of the Fruitvale school district, said
he was driving along Highway 80 when he saw a train on the tracks
and his eyes began to burn.
   ``We were driving and could smell the ammonia really well,'' he
said.
   ``The weather was real bad,'' said Travis. ``While I was driving,
there was real strong wind and some hail. I had to move a tree out
of the road at one point.''
</TEXT>
