<FILEID>AP-NR-11-26-88 2359EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PriestProtesters     11-26 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Priest Protesters,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Accuses Priest of Turning Away From Rights Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICENTE L. PANETTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRAGADO, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 people marched silently at
a Roman Catholic church Saturday to demand the ouster of a new
pastor that the town council has accused of ignoring human rights
abuses.
   ``I'm not going to send any of my kids to that church for
confession before someone who is capable of crucifying Christ,''
said Marta de la Torre, a 40-year-old housewife.
   The Rev. Christian von Wernich was leading a Mass for about 300
people inside while the protesters marched outside.
   The 16-member council that governs this town of 40,000 declared
von Wernich unwelcome and last week asked the church to remove him.
   ``The community of Bragado is not confronting the wise and
ancient church, only one of its priests who, by action or inaction,
lost his good reputation during the dark years of repression,'' the
council said in a statement issued Saturday.
   Von Wernich, a 50-year-old, balding man with a stern demeanor,
drove into this prosperous farm community about 125 miles west of
Buenos Aires on Nov. 17.
   He was met at the door of Santa Rosa de Lima church by about 500
people. Some shouted, ``Murderer! Murderer!'' and others carried
placards that said, ``We don't want torturers.''
   The heart of the complaints against von Wernich is that, as
chaplain for the Buenos Aires provincial police during the late
1970s, he visited detention centers where hundreds of young
Argentines were tortured and killed. Yet his critics say he never
denounced the police.
   The military and security forces at that time were trying to
stamp out an urban guerrilla movement.
   During the dictatorship that followed the overthrow of President
Isabel Peron in 1976, an estimated 9,000 Argentines disappeared and
were presumed executed, according to a government commission
appointed by President Raul Alfonsin.
   Argentina was ruled by three military juntas between Mrs. Peron's
ouster and Alfonsin's election in October 1983.
   Von Wernich until earlier this month served in the smaller
community of Norberto de la Riestra north of Bragado.
   He has in the past denied the accusations of his detractors.
During the past week, he has refused to comment to reporters.
   Von Wernich has his supporters. Attorney Sergio Tente said he
thinks the priest is being unfairly persecuted and those doing so
``should be excommunicated from the Catholic Church.''
   But many others side with Jose Idiart, 57, whose daughter was
arrested by security forces and never seen again.
   Idiart said von Wernich told the family on several occasions that
their daughter was well and would return. She never did.
   ``It's clear that von Wernich shielded himself behind his cassock
to collaborate with murderers,'' Idiart said.
   So far, the church has backed the priest. However, Bishop
Jeronimo Podesta hinted that it might transfer him, saying, ``A
priest repudiated by his flock cannot be their pastor.''
</TEXT>
