<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-Guerrillas     11-26 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Guerrillas,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nineteen Leftists, One Soldier Killed In Raid On Guerrilla Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops battled leftist guerrillas in a
remote area east of Bogota on Saturday, and 19 rebels and a soldier
were killed, a military commander said.
   The battle broke out after soldiers discovered the guerrilla camp
in the Sierra de la Mararena region in the remote eastern plains,
150 miles east of Bogota, Gen. Rafael Padilla Vergara, commander of
the army's 2nd Division, said on the RCN radio.
   He said the army found a clandestine landing strip and coca
plants, from which cocaine is cultivated, a sign the Colombian
Revolutionary Armed Forces guerrillas and cocaine traffickers were
working together in the area.
   He said the soldiers also found an arms cache that had once
belonged to the Colombian army. He did not say whether the weapons
had been stolen or captured.
   Colombian guerrillas often forge alliances with drug traffickers,
providing protection to the drug runners for a share of the huge
profits.
   ``Probably the landing strip is used for the transport of arms
with the destination to guerrillas and the export of cocaine grown
in this region,'' Padilla Vergara said.
   The attack was the first since President Virgilio Barco announced
emergency measures Friday to fight leftist rebels, right-wing
paramilitary groups and drug traffickers.
   Barco promised to increase the security forces and stiffen
penalties for terrorist-related killings.
   Colombian rebel armies have an estimated 10,000 members, and are
blamed for more than 2,000 deaths and nearly 500 kidnappings this
year alone.
</TEXT>
