<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BabySnatched 1stLd-Writethru a0595 11-26 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Snatched, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0595,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Infant Snatched From Hospital Found In Good Condition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1st graf with one graf and 8th graf, `Tieman said' with
two grafs to UPDATE with report that woman brought baby to a bar.
Subs grafs 11 to end, bgng `The suspects' with six grafs to UPDATE
with comment from mother saying she saw suspects in hospital.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sickly infant snatched from her
hospital bassinet was found in apparent good health Saturday after a
woman went to a bar to show off a baby she claimed was born only
hours earlier, police said.
   Two people were held Saturday on kidnapping charges in Washtenaw
County Jail in connection with the incident, Ann Arbor Police Sgt.
Jim Tieman said.
   The 4-pound, 8-ounce girl was reported taken at 6:35 p.m. Friday
from C.S. Mott Children's Hospital in Ann Arbor. She was recovered
about 11 a.m. Saturday at the suspects' apartment in Howell, about
20 miles away, Tieman said.
   Tieman would not release the suspects' names, but described the
woman as being in her 30s and the man as in his 40s. He said they
were not related to the baby's 17-year-old mother.
   The 2{-month-old infant, Debra Lynn Moore, was receiving
medication at the hospital for breathing problems when she was
taken. The premature infant also was hooked up to electronic
monitoring equipment and required feeding every three hours to
prevent dehydration.
   An alarm went off when she was removed from a bassinet Friday
evening, but the baby was gone when hospital workers reached the
room, said police Sgt. Mark Jones.
   ``She seems to be in good condition,'' said Catherine Cureton, a
spokeswoman for the University of Michigan Medical Center, which
operates Mott Hospital. ``She was doing remarkably well before this
happened and is doing well now.''
   Tieman said a caller Saturday morning notified the department
that the suspects showed up in Howell with the baby at 9:30 p.m.
Friday saying she had given birth to the baby at a hospital only
hours earlier.
   ``Everybody said who ... would bring a two-hour-old baby in the
bar,'' said John Cleary of Cleary's Pub, where the infant was taken
Friday night.
   Police investigating the tip went to the apartment and while
there, the suspects drove up with the baby sitting in a car seat.
   Tieman said he did not know the motive for the kidnapping.
   The baby's mother, Kimberly Sue Moore of Monroe, who was not at
the hospital when the baby was taken, said Saturday she thought she
saw the suspects Tuesday in the baby's ward.
   ``People have been following me around the hospital, and people
had been seeing my baby at the hospital that I didn't know,'' she
said. ``I've seen them up here. I believe they were the people who
were up here Tuesday asking to see my baby.''
   She said she notified hospital employees of the strangers.
   Debra was returned to the hospital about 1 p.m. Saturday, and it
was not known when the baby would be released, Cureton said.
   Debra's twin brother, in a nearby bassinet and receiving oxygen,
was unharmed, Tieman said. Breathing difficulties are not uncommon
in premature babies, whose lungs may not have matured before birth.
   The suspects were to appear in 15th District Court in Ann Arbor
on Monday.
</TEXT>
