<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DigestBriefs     11-26 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digest Briefs,0475</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Canada's strongest earthquake in 53 years
knocked out power and telephone service, buckled railroad tracks,
shook buildings and sent tremors from Michigan to Washington.
   About 50 people near the quake's epicenter at Chicoutimi, Quebec,
suffered minor cuts and bruises, but no serious injuries were
reported in Canada or in the United States. One American said he was
knocked out of his seat; others said windows rattled, dishes fell
from shelves and ceilings cracked.
   Seismologists said the quake registered 6.0 on the Richter scale,
enough to cause severe damage, but damage was relatively minor.
Janet Drysdale of the Geological Survey of Canada placed the
epicenter about 90 miles northwest of Quebec City and just east of
the St. Lawrence River along a minor fault zone.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo today asked the
nation to forgive his predecessor, Chun Doo-hwan, and promised
amnesty and compensation for political prisoners jailed under Chun's
rule.
   ``I will liquidate past wrongdoings and carry out bold reforms in
the government and governing party in the quest of a new era,'' Roh
said in a nationwide television address.
   Roh pledged a major shuffle of the government and governing
Democratic Justice Party and a revision of undemocratic laws to
prevent more abuses. Opposition parties immediately rejected Roh's
appeal and said Chun had to account fully for corruption and human
rights abuses under his seven-year rule. Opposition leaders said
Chun should be investigated by the National Assembly and a special
prosecutor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush should make a top
priority of slashing aid to farmers, particularly those subsidies
that reward farmers for high production, the conservative Heritage
Foundation think tank said.
   The report said farmers are generally better off than commonly
believed and should be forced to operate in a more competitive
environment with fewer government handouts.
   The Bush administration should develop a farm policy that would
``help American farmers break out (of a) cycle of dependence'' on
federal subsidies, Charles Grizzle wrote in the Heritage
Foundation's forthcoming policy guidebook. Grizzle, a former senior
official in the Agriculture Department, said the key to weaning
farmers from government aid is to ``decouple'' subsidy programs from
production requirements.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Retailers wallowing through the second year of a damaging slump
will have at least one brief, shining moment to recall from 1988.
   Christmas shoppers crowded stores around the country Friday in a
post-Thanksgiving rush worthy of its traditional billing as the
busiest day of the year for merchants.
   Malls and downtowns were crowded early with people racing to snap
up such hot-selling items as electronic gear, Nintendo video games,
cashmere sweaters, customized luggage, Barbie dolls and kitchen
appliances.
</TEXT>
